[SPEAKER_08]: We have our elections manager Melissa Ripley here I also see Henry Miller and the expenditure summary is $340,196 up $15,655 4.82% versus the prior year.

195
00:12:23,262 --> 00:12:30,547
[SPEAKER_08]: So over the last six months, obviously I'm the new election manager, and we're trying to streamline things and move things forward checking in the

196
00:12:40,458 --> 00:12:45,643
[SPEAKER_00]: checking at what we've done in the past and what we can do differently based on conferences I've gone to.

197
00:12:45,983 --> 00:12:50,548
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of the things we've done is we've purchased two secure election boxes.

198
00:12:50,708 --> 00:12:55,713
[SPEAKER_00]: One will be outside so that people can drive by and drop off their census and ballots.

199
00:12:56,513 --> 00:12:58,115
[SPEAKER_00]: The other one will be inside the building.

200
00:12:58,195 --> 00:13:01,278
[SPEAKER_00]: And again, the idea is for people to feel secure about the election.

201
00:13:02,419 --> 00:13:12,185
[SPEAKER_00]: We purchased two metal boxes that will be available and lockable during early voting just again to give people the sense that we are doing the right thing with their ballots.

202
00:13:14,167 --> 00:13:15,207
[SPEAKER_00]: We're working really hard.

203
00:13:15,287 --> 00:13:20,571
[SPEAKER_00]: We're soliciting for more election workers because we can never have enough election workers.

204
00:13:20,651 --> 00:13:21,512
[SPEAKER_00]: So here's my plug.

205
00:13:21,572 --> 00:13:24,874
[SPEAKER_00]: If you're watching and you want to be an election worker, please, please join us.

206
00:13:26,495 --> 00:13:27,956
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think we've done a really good job.

207
00:13:28,416 --> 00:13:29,057
[SPEAKER_00]: So thank you.

208
00:13:30,419 --> 00:13:37,825
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, we'll go to Councilor Carvillo.

209
00:13:38,646 --> 00:13:43,530
[SPEAKER_02]: We see there's a cutback on staff from a full-time senior clerk to a part-time clerk.

210
00:13:46,813 --> 00:13:49,975
[SPEAKER_00]: Ideally, we'd have a bazillion people working full-time for elections.

211
00:13:50,956 --> 00:13:57,341
[SPEAKER_00]: We're looking at streamlining our process, making sure that we're utilizing the city funds to the best of our ability.

212
00:13:58,360 --> 00:14:02,623
[SPEAKER_00]: We do have a part-time position that is in the play.

213
00:14:03,303 --> 00:14:06,486
[SPEAKER_00]: If for some reason we need to have a full-time person, we can certainly do that.

214
00:14:07,466 --> 00:14:13,630
[SPEAKER_00]: I think during the off times, we are slower, and so it doesn't make sense to have a full-time person in the office.

215
00:14:14,111 --> 00:14:21,616
[SPEAKER_00]: But after the elections, we will, after the first election, we'll look at what we have, and if we need to have a full-time person, we can make that change.

216
00:14:22,276 --> 00:14:27,460
[SPEAKER_02]: So when is the full-time going part-time?

217
00:14:28,885 --> 00:14:37,990
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, we have to put the job posting out, so as soon as the job posting goes out for the part-time person, we'll then... So, is there someone working in that position right now?

218
00:14:38,551 --> 00:14:38,651
[SPEAKER_00]: No.

219
00:14:38,751 --> 00:14:39,711
[SPEAKER_02]: Nobody working there?

220
00:14:39,751 --> 00:14:40,852
[SPEAKER_00]: Nobody working in the position now.

221
00:14:40,892 --> 00:14:51,098
[SPEAKER_00]: We do have one person who's coming in for about eight hours a week to help us in the short term, but they're not a permanent employee, they're just a temporary.

222
00:14:53,819 --> 00:14:55,280
[SPEAKER_02]: That is a union position, correct?

223
00:14:55,480 --> 00:14:56,301
[SPEAKER_00]: That is correct.

224
00:14:56,641 --> 00:14:58,262
[SPEAKER_02]: Is that a violation of the union protocol?

225
00:14:59,218 --> 00:15:00,200
[SPEAKER_00]: HR is working on that.

226
00:15:00,762 --> 00:15:04,731
[SPEAKER_00]: I am not privy to any of that, so I just let HR handle that because they're the experts.

227
00:15:06,114 --> 00:15:06,234
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

228
00:15:06,314 --> 00:15:08,539
[SPEAKER_02]: How are we on our staffing for the polls on election day?

229
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:11,201
[SPEAKER_00]: We are working on our staffing for our polls.

230
00:15:11,241 --> 00:15:15,703
[SPEAKER_00]: We sent a letter out to all of our election workers, seeing if they're coming back.

231
00:15:15,763 --> 00:15:17,104
[SPEAKER_00]: We do have some polls.

232
00:15:17,444 --> 00:15:20,025
[SPEAKER_00]: We've sent a letter out to both of the city parties.

233
00:15:20,485 --> 00:15:21,666
[SPEAKER_00]: We're waiting to hear back from them.

234
00:15:21,706 --> 00:15:24,067
[SPEAKER_00]: They have until June 15th to respond.

235
00:15:25,548 --> 00:15:27,849
[SPEAKER_00]: Six weeks out from the election, we have some flexibility.

236
00:15:27,889 --> 00:15:34,232
[SPEAKER_00]: If we don't have any additional workers, we can go outside of the city as long as they're registered voters in the state of Massachusetts.

237
00:15:34,727 --> 00:15:36,308
[SPEAKER_00]: So we're working on it.

238
00:15:36,368 --> 00:15:39,831
[SPEAKER_00]: It's an ever-evolving process and we're trying to recruit enough people.

239
00:15:41,092 --> 00:15:46,777
[SPEAKER_02]: I also see there was a 73% reduction in repair and maintenance of equipments.

240
00:15:47,418 --> 00:15:49,520
[SPEAKER_02]: Does that include our voting machines also?

241
00:15:49,980 --> 00:16:00,409
[SPEAKER_00]: So what we did was we moved that money to our contingency funds to hopefully sort of clean up the line items so we know what line items go where.

242
00:16:02,641 --> 00:16:06,825
[SPEAKER_00]: We have the Audemars machines, which we have a contract to have clean.

243
00:16:06,905 --> 00:16:08,606
[SPEAKER_00]: The state pays that contract for us.

244
00:16:09,807 --> 00:16:17,034
[SPEAKER_00]: With LHS, we pay for the yearly maintenance on LHS machines, but the yearly maintenance isn't that great.

245
00:16:18,467 --> 00:16:19,988
[SPEAKER_02]: So the contingency plan has $52,000 in it?

246
00:16:20,008 --> 00:16:20,709
[SPEAKER_02]: Yep.

247
00:16:21,650 --> 00:16:24,052
[SPEAKER_02]: That's 100% more than it had last year?

248
00:16:24,392 --> 00:16:38,243
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, because we moved things from other line items into that budget just so that we could make sure that all of the LHS items, which are the contingency items, are in one place so it's easier to track going forward, so we can see what we're paying where.

249
00:16:39,504 --> 00:16:42,307
[SPEAKER_02]: And what is the status of our census now?

250
00:16:43,324 --> 00:16:47,666
[SPEAKER_00]: Right now, we've received most of the census that we're gonna receive back.

251
00:16:47,726 --> 00:16:55,089
[SPEAKER_00]: We sent out 15,000 postcards letting people know that they have been moved from active status to inactive status.

252
00:16:55,569 --> 00:17:00,731
[SPEAKER_00]: What that means is if they go to the polls and they haven't reactivated themselves, they do have to show ID.

253
00:17:01,231 --> 00:17:03,592
[SPEAKER_00]: We will never turn somebody away from the polls.

254
00:17:03,792 --> 00:17:05,073
[SPEAKER_00]: Everybody will be able to vote.

255
00:17:05,173 --> 00:17:09,815
[SPEAKER_00]: It's just gonna take a couple minutes more if they don't return those inactivation cards.

256
00:17:10,545 --> 00:17:14,328
[SPEAKER_02]: And my last question, the clerks in your office still haven't gotten a raise either, correct?

257
00:17:14,949 --> 00:17:15,369
[SPEAKER_00]: Say that again?

258
00:17:15,389 --> 00:17:17,271
[SPEAKER_02]: The clerks in your office have not gotten a raise.

259
00:17:18,172 --> 00:17:21,535
[SPEAKER_00]: That is correct, they're waiting for the union raise to happen.

260
00:17:22,296 --> 00:17:30,343
[SPEAKER_00]: However, I will say that Joan Lamoni did get a promotion recently, so she is now the head clerk instead of the senior clerk.

261
00:17:33,546 --> 00:17:34,687
[SPEAKER_02]: And that's it for me at the moment, thank you.

262
00:17:35,047 --> 00:17:36,028
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

263
00:17:36,308 --> 00:17:37,049
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Madam President.

264
00:17:38,721 --> 00:17:41,102
[SPEAKER_15]: Chris Ripley, thank you.

265
00:17:42,323 --> 00:17:48,666
[SPEAKER_15]: Not to be critical, but I think that this is something that this council worked very hard to make sure that this department was staffed appropriately.

266
00:17:49,607 --> 00:17:57,451
[SPEAKER_15]: We've had some issues in the past, and we worked diligently to make sure that your position was here to lead us the right way.

267
00:17:57,651 --> 00:17:58,472
[SPEAKER_00]: And I appreciate that.

268
00:17:58,572 --> 00:18:02,874
[SPEAKER_15]: And I appreciate you, but what I don't appreciate is that the

269
00:18:04,843 --> 00:18:06,728
[SPEAKER_15]: the lack of fight for more staff.

270
00:18:06,949 --> 00:18:09,537
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, to think that

271
00:18:10,948 --> 00:18:18,150
[SPEAKER_15]: to mention that your staff, there's not enough to do when we're looking at three major elections that are coming up in the next couple of years, right?

272
00:18:18,910 --> 00:18:23,511
[SPEAKER_15]: And the questions that arise in just that period, it's like a firefighter.

273
00:18:24,171 --> 00:18:30,672
[SPEAKER_15]: They could sit in their fire station for 10 days without a fire, then all of a sudden have three major blazes and they earn their pay.

274
00:18:31,152 --> 00:18:34,973
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think this council has shown our commitment to make sure that

275
00:18:36,214 --> 00:18:37,275
[SPEAKER_15]: it's staffed correctly.

276
00:18:38,577 --> 00:18:50,209
[SPEAKER_15]: As a municipal employee, I know one of the big things we talk about is when we meet with a city clerk, city solicitor, that we're very cautious of when we

277
00:18:51,155 --> 00:19:00,485
[SPEAKER_15]: move a position from a full-time to a part-time position, making sure that it's not union, because there are huge liabilities and labor laws that affect that.

278
00:19:00,565 --> 00:19:06,211
[SPEAKER_15]: So I will be honest with you, this will be one of the things that I look at when it comes to voting on the budget.

279
00:19:07,372 --> 00:19:16,835
[SPEAKER_15]: because I think for this council that has put so much effort and really making sure that this office is fully staffed and fully funded, I'm not going to quit now.

280
00:19:18,036 --> 00:19:21,217
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think that, you know, you have one of the strongest supporters behind you.

281
00:19:21,697 --> 00:19:31,360
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'd love to get his input later on, and Mr. Miller in that, you know, he's walked the walk every day for the last thousand years here, making sure the elections are run the proper way.

282
00:19:32,440 --> 00:19:37,462
[SPEAKER_15]: I can't see him not being a supporter, not being being a supporter of this.

283
00:19:37,522 --> 00:19:46,286
[SPEAKER_15]: So this might be something that I look at that I'll ask the mayor to make this a full funded position because I, you know, I know you're part of the team.

284
00:19:46,366 --> 00:19:49,427
[SPEAKER_15]: So I'm not I'm not putting in the spot because I'm on that other side.

285
00:19:49,847 --> 00:19:51,928
[SPEAKER_15]: So I don't expect you to say George,

286
00:19:52,949 --> 00:19:55,270
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, this is we're all right.

287
00:19:55,291 --> 00:19:55,791
[SPEAKER_15]: We're great.

288
00:19:55,831 --> 00:19:56,351
[SPEAKER_15]: I know we're not.

289
00:19:56,451 --> 00:20:02,396
[SPEAKER_15]: But I will let you know from my personal opinion, I think for a few reasons that this position has to be funded.

290
00:20:02,436 --> 00:20:03,197
[SPEAKER_15]: So thank you.

291
00:20:04,118 --> 00:20:06,299
[SPEAKER_00]: If I can explain something.

292
00:20:06,760 --> 00:20:09,682
[SPEAKER_00]: The part time position is part time.

293
00:20:10,503 --> 00:20:13,285
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, in theory, during the elections,

294
00:20:13,788 --> 00:20:15,589
[SPEAKER_00]: the part-time position will increase.

295
00:20:15,649 --> 00:20:24,294
[SPEAKER_00]: As long as we keep the steady number of hours throughout the year, we are able to have the person come in.

296
00:20:24,374 --> 00:20:31,759
[SPEAKER_00]: So I created a spreadsheet that basically shows during slow times that the person would work 15 hours a week.

297
00:20:32,219 --> 00:20:38,363
[SPEAKER_00]: But during busy times during the election, they're gonna have to work 35 hours a week in order to help us.

298
00:20:38,863 --> 00:20:44,741
[SPEAKER_00]: So I understand your concern about not having a full-time person year-round, but I do think that...

299
00:20:45,932 --> 00:20:53,697
[SPEAKER_00]: We're going to go into the first election, the preliminary election, if we have one, making sure that we understand what's going on.

300
00:20:54,338 --> 00:20:57,120
[SPEAKER_00]: And after that election, we can then make a determination.

301
00:20:57,140 --> 00:21:00,442
[SPEAKER_00]: But I understand your concerns.

302
00:21:00,662 --> 00:21:02,063
[SPEAKER_15]: It just doesn't sound too fair, does it?

303
00:21:02,383 --> 00:21:10,389
[SPEAKER_15]: So let's bring in a lesser employee and have them work 10 hours or 15 hours a week, then all of a sudden, we're going to inundate them when we need them.

304
00:21:13,078 --> 00:21:18,350
[SPEAKER_15]: as a person that's for labor, that doesn't pass the smell test for me.

305
00:21:18,491 --> 00:21:19,092
[SPEAKER_15]: I just think that

306
00:21:20,009 --> 00:21:23,491
[SPEAKER_15]: If we're going to, if we're going to, if someone's going to commit to us, we should commit to them.

307
00:21:24,311 --> 00:21:35,658
[SPEAKER_15]: If we've, if we've committed and agreed upon this, this mayor as, as, as signed off and understood that they're now union employees, you have to follow those union rules.

308
00:21:36,138 --> 00:21:42,701
[SPEAKER_15]: So I don't, you know, I understand you, like I said, I understand your, your, your position, but at the same time,

309
00:21:44,461 --> 00:21:50,772
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't, it doesn't, it doesn't give me the warm and fuzzies that we're going to bring someone in for $12 a week.

310
00:21:51,153 --> 00:21:53,858
[SPEAKER_15]: And then when it comes to most important time, we're going to give them 35 hours.

311
00:21:54,379 --> 00:21:56,623
[SPEAKER_15]: It just, I just don't think that's fair in many different ways.

312
00:21:56,643 --> 00:21:57,384
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't think it's fair to you.

313
00:21:58,191 --> 00:21:59,772
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, and I do understand that.

314
00:21:59,912 --> 00:22:04,133
[SPEAKER_00]: One thing I will add is we do have an advanced team that comes in prior to the election.

315
00:22:04,273 --> 00:22:15,337
[SPEAKER_00]: So for early voting, vote by mail, and sending out all the vote by mail applications, we have about five to six people who are there to assist us and make sure that everything goes out smoothly.

316
00:22:16,598 --> 00:22:18,659
[SPEAKER_00]: Just to give you that information.

317
00:22:18,819 --> 00:22:21,640
[SPEAKER_00]: But I understand your concerns and I appreciate those.

318
00:22:22,120 --> 00:22:22,440
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

319
00:22:22,460 --> 00:22:26,782
[SPEAKER_15]: So Madam President, if I could to the clerk,

320
00:22:27,753 --> 00:22:53,509
[SPEAKER_15]: Can we make sure we make that part of the minutes that we ask the, I can't say legal opinion because we don't have a solicitor, but the opinion of our HR director who just started a few weeks ago to make sure that this isn't going to bite us in the keister for another unfair labor lawsuit by hiring a part-time employee in a union position, full-time union position.

321
00:22:53,869 --> 00:22:54,069
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

322
00:22:56,764 --> 00:23:00,545
[SPEAKER_08]: Madam Chief of staff, do you have clarity you can offer to that situation?

323
00:23:01,145 --> 00:23:04,286
[SPEAKER_07]: Through you, Madam President, to Councilor Scarapelli.

324
00:23:04,826 --> 00:23:10,448
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Scarapelli, the human resources director has contacted the union to discuss this matter.

325
00:23:10,568 --> 00:23:15,089
[SPEAKER_07]: So I just want everyone to know that we're having those conversations.

326
00:23:15,569 --> 00:23:16,830
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

327
00:23:16,870 --> 00:23:18,050
[SPEAKER_07]: Go to Vice President Behrs.

328
00:23:18,850 --> 00:23:19,790
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Madam President.

329
00:23:19,870 --> 00:23:21,171
[SPEAKER_20]: Thanks, Melissa, for being here.

330
00:23:21,931 --> 00:23:23,611
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm sorry I didn't get my questions to you sooner.

331
00:23:23,631 --> 00:23:23,952
[SPEAKER_00]: That's okay.

332
00:23:28,212 --> 00:23:34,513
[SPEAKER_20]: So my understanding, A, if I look at the budget, we were way over this year.

333
00:23:34,933 --> 00:23:44,535
[SPEAKER_20]: We were at 380, 380 plus, and it's going down to 340, which makes me think that there was a lot of work that needed to be done this year.

334
00:23:44,996 --> 00:23:54,358
[SPEAKER_20]: And also, my understanding of how this, of course, it's under the new election commission to move from the registrar of voters, but between this, the budget being so over for FY23,

335
00:23:57,425 --> 00:24:08,334
[SPEAKER_20]: And in this upcoming fiscal year, we're gonna have three elections, not two, like we had in the previous fiscal year between the preliminary general, maybe three, preliminary general and the presidential primary.

336
00:24:08,855 --> 00:24:23,868
[SPEAKER_20]: And that back in 2020, prior to this new arrangement, when we had the registrar and the clerk's office, we had four full-time, basically four FTE staff working on elections, plus the elections coordinator who would come in

337
00:24:25,053 --> 00:24:27,576
[SPEAKER_20]: know, for full time for an extensive period of the year.

338
00:24:27,656 --> 00:24:33,403
[SPEAKER_20]: So at least four and a half FT, if not a little bit more, this would bring you down to two and a half FT.

339
00:24:34,124 --> 00:24:40,532
[SPEAKER_20]: So that's the piece where it's not not really fitting in my head is that we are going from almost five people to two and a half people.

340
00:24:41,133 --> 00:24:44,176
[SPEAKER_20]: The budget was over last year, we're actually gonna have more elections this year.

341
00:24:45,523 --> 00:24:46,624
[SPEAKER_20]: And that makes me really worried.

342
00:24:47,265 --> 00:24:55,752
[SPEAKER_20]: So, you know, if you could explicate a little bit more how you think you're going to be able to do so much more with so much less, that would be helpful.

343
00:24:56,193 --> 00:24:56,433
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes.

344
00:24:56,633 --> 00:25:02,999
[SPEAKER_00]: So I do know that there were three full-time people in the office and I wasn't here.

345
00:25:03,099 --> 00:25:05,101
[SPEAKER_00]: So I, I, this is just what I'm gathering.

346
00:25:05,161 --> 00:25:07,003
[SPEAKER_00]: There were three full-time people in the office.

347
00:25:07,803 --> 00:25:09,585
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, the fourth person actually was,

348
00:25:10,164 --> 00:25:18,028
[SPEAKER_00]: here during the elections, part-time, full-time during the elections, and then was not here on off election times.

349
00:25:18,468 --> 00:25:21,229
[SPEAKER_00]: So that would give you three and a half employees.

350
00:25:21,249 --> 00:25:25,391
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's just my understanding.

351
00:25:25,551 --> 00:25:26,191
[SPEAKER_11]: Plus the clerk.

352
00:25:26,872 --> 00:25:28,072
[SPEAKER_00]: Plus the clerk.

353
00:25:28,252 --> 00:25:29,013
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

354
00:25:30,083 --> 00:25:38,676
[SPEAKER_00]: So, that being said, yes we are, we are down people but I think some of that is, it's an efficiency thing.

355
00:25:39,236 --> 00:25:42,982
[SPEAKER_00]: I do think that the experience that I bring to the table will help us

356
00:25:43,422 --> 00:25:47,106
[SPEAKER_00]: with efficiency, we're getting stuff ready in advance for the election.

357
00:25:48,468 --> 00:25:56,897
[SPEAKER_00]: We purchased, part of the reason why the budget was so high over this year, was we purchased things that we needed in order to meet the Mass General Laws.

358
00:25:57,278 --> 00:26:04,346
[SPEAKER_00]: So for instance, when we have vote by mail, applications, ballots, we have to keep all of those.

359
00:26:04,960 --> 00:26:12,242
[SPEAKER_00]: So we bought secure boxes, ballot tote boxes in order to make sure that our election, the election integrity is intact.

360
00:26:13,242 --> 00:26:19,044
[SPEAKER_00]: So those were some of the pre-purchases that we made in anticipation of the fall elections.

361
00:26:21,345 --> 00:26:30,027
[SPEAKER_00]: I do think that, you know, moving Joan Lamoni into a higher position will help because she's very experienced in the elections in Medford.

362
00:26:30,367 --> 00:26:32,828
[SPEAKER_00]: So she offers an experience that I don't have.

363
00:26:34,526 --> 00:26:43,969
[SPEAKER_00]: But I do think that as we move the professionalism forward in the office and we're learning from other people's experiences, we're able to more efficiently respond to things.

364
00:26:44,789 --> 00:26:46,390
[SPEAKER_00]: For instance, poll pads.

365
00:26:47,250 --> 00:26:49,851
[SPEAKER_00]: So we have not used the full capacity of poll pads.

366
00:26:50,311 --> 00:26:57,974
[SPEAKER_00]: In past elections, when we've had people who've had to show IDs for affirmations, if they're inactive, we've typed everything in.

367
00:26:58,574 --> 00:27:00,474
[SPEAKER_00]: So you've typed in about 300 plus people

