01:12:26,669 --> 01:12:31,596
[SPEAKER_18]: assistant secretary now and now Darlene is part time 20 hours a week.

892
01:12:32,477 --> 01:12:35,401
[SPEAKER_18]: And we were pretty busy in the office.

893
01:12:35,781 --> 01:12:43,551
[SPEAKER_15]: So maybe that might be one of the reasons why we can't we can't go out and secure more vets that need that need the assistance potentially.

894
01:12:44,813 --> 01:12:52,302
[SPEAKER_18]: Yeah, I tried to get out and I have met with several like social workers that have brought some people up to my attention.

895
01:12:53,183 --> 01:13:01,633
[SPEAKER_18]: I let them know what is required, what kind of evidence I need, discharge paperwork, and I don't hear back from them and there's only so much that I can do.

896
01:13:01,773 --> 01:13:02,874
[SPEAKER_15]: Right, right.

897
01:13:03,255 --> 01:13:04,416
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you work very closely with

898
01:13:05,417 --> 01:13:09,719
[SPEAKER_15]: with the different departments here in the city that can assist you with that?

899
01:13:09,759 --> 01:13:17,441
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, I know that this with the social work, we have a very, very robust communication department in the mayor's office.

900
01:13:17,922 --> 01:13:26,645
[SPEAKER_15]: Are we using their expertise and trying to find strategies to reach out to to method veterans and seeing if maybe they can come up with a plan?

901
01:13:26,665 --> 01:13:27,765
[SPEAKER_15]: I think that's their profession.

902
01:13:27,845 --> 01:13:32,207
[SPEAKER_15]: So have we thought of a plan to maybe, you know, work with them?

903
01:13:33,005 --> 01:13:33,825
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, we could do that.

904
01:13:34,265 --> 01:13:36,506
[SPEAKER_18]: And we'll do that or have continued to do.

905
01:13:36,526 --> 01:13:37,766
[SPEAKER_18]: I appreciate that.

906
01:13:37,806 --> 01:13:41,607
[SPEAKER_15]: So I like that, like I said, I think that you're so valuable.

907
01:13:41,707 --> 01:13:53,291
[SPEAKER_15]: But when you look at veterans, either it's, you know, they're too proud to come to the office, or they're just not don't know how to get there, whether they're, you know,

908
01:13:54,891 --> 01:14:00,796
[SPEAKER_15]: you know, an older veteran or a younger veteran, I think it's, you know, very similar situation.

909
01:14:00,856 --> 01:14:11,365
[SPEAKER_15]: So, um, I mean, we're seeing it, we're talking to our friends at the different VFWs and the American Legions, and they're seeing a huge drop in participation.

910
01:14:11,425 --> 01:14:14,327
[SPEAKER_15]: And that, that's alarming because it's more of a social aspect.

911
01:14:14,767 --> 01:14:22,614
[SPEAKER_15]: So it's kind of frightening that, that veterans aren't finding relief with their brothers and sisters at a social situation.

912
01:14:22,654 --> 01:14:23,494
[SPEAKER_15]: But, um,

913
01:14:24,386 --> 01:14:30,450
[SPEAKER_15]: you know, if there's anything that this council can do, you know, to hold any events or look to see if we can promote things.

914
01:14:30,970 --> 01:14:35,453
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we all need to find a way to really boost those numbers.

915
01:14:35,513 --> 01:14:48,462
[SPEAKER_15]: And, you know, I personally think that you having a full time secretary, because I believe from what I remember in the past, the past Veterans Affairs directors that we've met with, their biggest concern is doing all that paperwork.

916
01:14:49,162 --> 01:14:51,384
[SPEAKER_15]: And the most important person that's got to be out there

917
01:14:52,084 --> 01:14:55,846
[SPEAKER_15]: you know, a lot of people, uh, showing their face and saying, Hey, we have this office here.

918
01:14:56,346 --> 01:15:03,990
[SPEAKER_15]: It's stuck behind the desk in an office fellow paperwork that a trained, um, administrative assistant can do for you a secretary.

919
01:15:04,051 --> 01:15:12,535
[SPEAKER_15]: So I'd really like to see, you know, it's not a lot of money if we're paying a part time, you know, adding a couple $1000 to get a full time position.

920
01:15:12,955 --> 01:15:15,076
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we'll pay huge dividends in your office.

921
01:15:15,116 --> 01:15:16,377
[SPEAKER_15]: So thank you so much.

922
01:15:16,757 --> 01:15:17,018
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

923
01:15:21,977 --> 01:15:23,037
[SPEAKER_19]: Good Council, how are you doing?

924
01:15:23,057 --> 01:15:23,818
[SPEAKER_19]: Great, thanks for coming tonight.

925
01:15:24,878 --> 01:15:28,259
[SPEAKER_19]: How many veterans have you been able to identify here in the city?

926
01:15:32,341 --> 01:15:33,201
[SPEAKER_18]: Roughly was 1700.

927
01:15:33,622 --> 01:15:46,487
[SPEAKER_18]: The state sent out a roster of those that are receiving some sort of benefit from the from the Department of Veterans Affairs at the federal level, and that was around 700.

928
01:15:46,567 --> 01:15:46,867
[SPEAKER_18]: So there's

929
01:15:52,237 --> 01:16:01,723
[SPEAKER_18]: everything depends on somebody identifying themselves as a veteran and then me looking at their discharge and seeing if they're qualified for anything.

930
01:16:02,744 --> 01:16:10,649
[SPEAKER_18]: So other than what I was able to find out just online was the population was estimated at 1,700.

931
01:16:10,809 --> 01:16:19,154
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

932
01:16:20,195 --> 01:16:21,636
[SPEAKER_08]: Any other questions from the council?

933
01:16:23,258 --> 01:16:24,879
[SPEAKER_08]: Seeing none, thank you so much for being here.

934
01:16:24,899 --> 01:16:25,639
[SPEAKER_15]: Appreciate it.

935
01:16:25,659 --> 01:16:26,539
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

936
01:16:27,260 --> 01:16:30,281
[SPEAKER_08]: We will go to Assessor on page 117.

937
01:16:30,501 --> 01:16:34,302
[SPEAKER_08]: We have Ted Costigan, Chief Assessor.

938
01:16:34,542 --> 01:16:37,584
[SPEAKER_08]: We haven't met yet, so I'm assuming that's the right guess.

939
01:16:38,464 --> 01:16:40,245
[SPEAKER_08]: Expenditures, $559,637 minus $12,650, or minus 2.21% versus the prior year.

940
01:16:40,265 --> 01:16:41,385
[SPEAKER_08]: If you want to give us an overview, and welcome.

941
01:16:49,348 --> 01:16:51,770
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, good evening, Council is privileged to be here.

942
01:16:52,591 --> 01:17:02,901
[SPEAKER_01]: Our office is responsible for equitably valuing the roughly 17,000 real estate parcels in the city as well as the over 1000 personal property accounts.

943
01:17:04,202 --> 01:17:10,268
[SPEAKER_01]: We're particularly keen on picking up new growth off of our hundreds of millions of dollars in building permits we review every year.

944
01:17:11,129 --> 01:17:15,035
[SPEAKER_01]: as you know, new growth is revenue to the city that's new in the year we find it.

945
01:17:15,976 --> 01:17:24,929
[SPEAKER_01]: The office, you know, is anticipating a levy of around $139.6 million this year, which, as you know, is the majority of our budget.

946
01:17:25,910 --> 01:17:36,819
[SPEAKER_01]: We're doing a good job with our outreach to veterans and to the elderly, making sure we have fulfilled all the personal exemptions that Medford residents might have.

947
01:17:37,580 --> 01:17:49,669
[SPEAKER_01]: Talking to my colleagues in other communities, the fact that we have 350 people who are low-income elderly veterans or blind individuals who are receiving personal exemptions is an exceptional number even for a city this size.

948
01:17:50,786 --> 01:18:01,408
[SPEAKER_01]: We're continuing to give great customer service with our staff to Medford residents who come in for motor vehicle excise abatements or want to talk about their real estate property in the city.

949
01:18:02,509 --> 01:18:14,771
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm seeing a strong industrial core in Medford, a strong apartment class, and a residential class is still doing very well from a valuation perspective going into fiscal year 24.

950
01:18:14,831 --> 01:18:16,752
[SPEAKER_01]: Happy to take any of your questions.

951
01:18:17,855 --> 01:18:18,455
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

952
01:18:18,515 --> 01:18:19,436
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Carvajal.

953
01:18:19,516 --> 01:18:21,718
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

954
01:18:21,838 --> 01:18:23,559
[SPEAKER_02]: I want to thank you for being here and welcome to Medford.

955
01:18:24,099 --> 01:18:25,180
[SPEAKER_02]: I've got a couple of questions for you.

956
01:18:25,520 --> 01:18:33,725
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you give me some information on the abatements granted and the allowance for the abatement balance that we have for the last few years?

957
01:18:33,745 --> 01:18:37,008
[SPEAKER_02]: You don't have to give it to me tonight, but if you could send it to the council.

958
01:18:37,028 --> 01:18:37,328
[SPEAKER_02]: Absolutely.

959
01:18:37,348 --> 01:18:38,509
[SPEAKER_02]: From 20 to 23, that would be really appreciated.

960
01:18:45,310 --> 01:18:50,233
[SPEAKER_02]: I see there's a $500,000 allowance for abatements for the overlaid reserve.

961
01:18:51,474 --> 01:18:52,895
[SPEAKER_02]: Is that figure too low?

962
01:18:52,935 --> 01:18:54,156
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you feel that's enough money in there?

963
01:18:55,957 --> 01:18:57,358
[SPEAKER_01]: If I don't miss the mark, it's not too low.

964
01:18:57,778 --> 01:19:02,821
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm hoping to do a good job this year with the valuation that we're doing for fiscal year 24.

965
01:19:02,901 --> 01:19:04,162
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm looking at all the income models.

966
01:19:05,883 --> 01:19:09,505
[SPEAKER_01]: My hope is that that is a very reasonable number for abatements.

967
01:19:12,898 --> 01:19:22,506
[SPEAKER_02]: In fiscal 23, we were under our levy limit, 131,972, versus the number should be 133,790.

968
01:19:23,808 --> 01:19:31,374
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you have the correct tax rate for us?

969
01:19:31,775 --> 01:19:32,675
[SPEAKER_02]: Could you repeat that?

970
01:19:32,715 --> 01:19:32,956
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm sorry.

971
01:19:32,976 --> 01:19:33,796
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm sorry?

972
01:19:34,097 --> 01:19:35,258
[SPEAKER_02]: I didn't understand the question.

973
01:19:35,278 --> 01:19:35,858
[SPEAKER_02]: Could you repeat that?

974
01:19:35,898 --> 01:19:40,002
[SPEAKER_02]: He says, we seem to be under the levy limit.

975
01:19:41,059 --> 01:19:43,421
[SPEAKER_02]: I know we tell people we tax to the max, but we really don't.

976
01:19:44,522 --> 01:19:45,683
[SPEAKER_02]: The real levy limit is $133,790.

977
01:19:45,963 --> 01:19:52,788
[SPEAKER_02]: Our levy limit is $131,972 for fiscal year 23.

978
01:19:53,489 --> 01:19:54,650
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

979
01:19:55,610 --> 01:19:57,432
[SPEAKER_02]: Have you projected a new tax rate yet?

980
01:19:58,933 --> 01:20:01,735
[SPEAKER_02]: No, I have to have the valuation done to do the tax rate for next year.

981
01:20:01,755 --> 01:20:02,456
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

982
01:20:03,436 --> 01:20:07,780
[SPEAKER_02]: And pilot agreements we have.

983
01:20:09,980 --> 01:20:11,461
[SPEAKER_02]: For 23, I see a projection of 2.5 million versus 22.

984
01:20:11,501 --> 01:20:12,061
[SPEAKER_02]: There was 3.3 million.

985
01:20:12,141 --> 01:20:12,982
[SPEAKER_02]: Where is the difference?

986
01:20:22,774 --> 01:20:25,275
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm gonna have to review the pilot expectations.

987
01:20:25,836 --> 01:20:27,937
[SPEAKER_01]: I've just talked to the housing director today.

988
01:20:28,337 --> 01:20:33,560
[SPEAKER_01]: They're sending their fiscal year 23 pilot funding over in the next week.

989
01:20:34,261 --> 01:20:35,982
[SPEAKER_01]: I additionally have an MVDC meeting.

990
01:20:36,002 --> 01:20:40,785
[SPEAKER_01]: So we'll be getting the funding from them the week of June 19th.

991
01:20:40,825 --> 01:20:42,686
[SPEAKER_01]: So those are the two largest ones.

992
01:20:43,546 --> 01:20:49,670
[SPEAKER_01]: From a budgetary perspective, I'd have to ask our finance team as to why they lowered the expectation there.

993
01:20:50,790 --> 01:20:53,471
[SPEAKER_02]: that we can make that part of the report that we can get.

994
01:20:53,511 --> 01:20:54,371
[SPEAKER_02]: We can get those answers.

995
01:20:54,551 --> 01:20:54,751
[SPEAKER_02]: Yep.

996
01:20:55,312 --> 01:20:55,532
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

997
01:20:56,892 --> 01:20:57,192
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

998
01:20:57,972 --> 01:21:02,194
[SPEAKER_08]: Uh, uh, so probably vice president bears, but he's not there.

999
01:21:02,374 --> 01:21:04,454
[SPEAKER_15]: So well, well, thank you, Madam President.

1000
01:21:04,834 --> 01:21:05,355
[SPEAKER_15]: Welcome method.

1001
01:21:05,395 --> 01:21:07,915
[SPEAKER_15]: Appreciate you taking this, uh, this position.

1002
01:21:08,015 --> 01:21:10,456
[SPEAKER_15]: So I very simple question.

1003
01:21:10,736 --> 01:21:12,957
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll ask every department staffing wise.

1004
01:21:13,697 --> 01:21:14,757
[SPEAKER_15]: Um, where do you stand?

1005
01:21:14,817 --> 01:21:17,778
[SPEAKER_15]: And are you are you in need?

1006
01:21:18,058 --> 01:21:19,179
[SPEAKER_15]: Or do you find it very,

1007
01:21:20,310 --> 01:21:22,371
[SPEAKER_15]: but do you find it adequate what you have right now?

1008
01:21:22,911 --> 01:21:25,552
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I have a great staff.

1009
01:21:25,572 --> 01:21:29,534
[SPEAKER_01]: We're four busy individuals every day.

1010
01:21:30,615 --> 01:21:37,237
[SPEAKER_01]: Additionally, we have a part-time sort of ARPA-funded position that's very helpful for our field work.

1011
01:21:37,838 --> 01:21:40,219
[SPEAKER_01]: That is a request I made, again, going into fiscal year 24.

1012
01:21:40,539 --> 01:21:43,140
[SPEAKER_01]: It's the last ARPA year we can have for revenue replacement.

1013
01:21:43,160 --> 01:21:44,080
[SPEAKER_01]: That's going to be crucial.

1014
01:21:44,861 --> 01:21:47,382
[SPEAKER_01]: And if that goes through, I think we're going to be in really good shape.

1015
01:21:48,183 --> 01:21:53,568
[SPEAKER_15]: All right, so we're hoping in 2025, that might be a full time position ask because it looks like we need it.

1016
01:21:54,008 --> 01:21:55,750
[SPEAKER_15]: That would be one of a lot of changes in Medford.

1017
01:21:55,810 --> 01:22:01,195
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think this is one one department that makes us money when we work.

1018
01:22:01,375 --> 01:22:03,877
[SPEAKER_15]: So it's very important that we fund these positions.

1019
01:22:04,858 --> 01:22:05,018
[SPEAKER_15]: Yep.

1020
01:22:05,038 --> 01:22:05,399
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1021
01:22:06,379 --> 01:22:06,740
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1022
01:22:08,341 --> 01:22:09,803
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Collins, then we'll go to Councilor Behrs.

1023
01:22:11,027 --> 01:22:11,688
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for tomorrow.

1024
01:22:11,988 --> 01:22:14,050
[SPEAKER_05]: Thanks for being here and nice to meet you.

1025
01:22:14,630 --> 01:22:16,832
[SPEAKER_05]: Just a super quick question probably.

1026
01:22:16,852 --> 01:22:20,456
[SPEAKER_05]: I just wanted to make sure I was clear on the

1027
01:22:21,642 --> 01:22:23,703
[SPEAKER_05]: reduction in ordinary expenses.

1028
01:22:23,743 --> 01:22:28,725
[SPEAKER_05]: I see in the highlights it says ordinary went down by 50% looking at the line item breakdown.

1029
01:22:28,745 --> 01:22:35,487
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't see anything so drastic so I was just wondering if one of those was off or if you did see any dramatic decreases in ordinary expenses.

1030
01:22:35,567 --> 01:22:37,008
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I think that was a typo.

1031
01:22:37,948 --> 01:22:40,729
[SPEAKER_01]: The ordinary expense is down 2.2% year over year.

1032
01:22:43,653 --> 01:22:44,754
[SPEAKER_01]: So no drastic changes.

1033
01:22:44,794 --> 01:22:47,256
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm sorry, total expenses down 2%, ordinary 11%.

1034
01:22:47,617 --> 01:22:49,358
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's not a 50% reduction.

1035
01:22:50,800 --> 01:22:51,060
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1036
01:22:52,702 --> 01:22:53,302
[SPEAKER_08]: President Behrs.

1037
01:22:53,582 --> 01:22:54,403
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Madam President.

1038
01:22:55,784 --> 01:22:56,165
[SPEAKER_20]: Welcome.

1039
01:22:56,525 --> 01:22:56,865
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

1040
01:22:57,266 --> 01:22:57,866
[SPEAKER_20]: Good to meet you.

1041
01:22:59,548 --> 01:23:02,431
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't have huge questions about your budget.

1042
01:23:02,571 --> 01:23:08,917
[SPEAKER_20]: My main question about the budget is just, is there anything that you were looking for or will be looking for in the future that's not being funded?

1043
01:23:10,260 --> 01:23:14,723
[SPEAKER_01]: I think as we're going into the new economy, AI is a big part of this.

1044
01:23:15,183 --> 01:23:26,870
[SPEAKER_01]: It's in the news, buzzwords, but obviously from a valuation perspective, there's going to be tools that might come on, might be innovative that would really help us in that growth number.

1045
01:23:27,231 --> 01:23:28,511
[SPEAKER_01]: That's what I'm aiming towards.

1046
01:23:28,571 --> 01:23:35,055
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm at a $2.5 million figure, and that's with the review of 1,000 building permits.

1047
01:23:36,357 --> 01:23:44,641
[SPEAKER_01]: AI that can have me do that faster, whether it's detection technology or whatever else, that would be an area that I could see in future years.

1048
01:23:45,021 --> 01:23:52,364
[SPEAKER_20]: You just won an award for the first person to mention AI in my four budgets.

1049
01:23:53,305 --> 01:23:54,165
[SPEAKER_20]: My two questions.

1050
01:23:54,445 --> 01:23:56,746
[SPEAKER_20]: One, exemptions.

1051
01:23:57,247 --> 01:24:04,230
[SPEAKER_20]: We've had a lot of conversations with past folks in your office about residential exemption, about maxing out senior exemption, et cetera.

1052
01:24:06,219 --> 01:24:07,819
[SPEAKER_20]: Just kind of a general thought from you.

1053
01:24:09,720 --> 01:24:16,481
[SPEAKER_20]: If we were to consider it, how do you think that would affect the way that you operate in your office or the way that we raise the levy?

1054
01:24:17,041 --> 01:24:22,943
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you have concerns off the bat or do you think it's really more of a policy call that we might implement effectively?

1055
01:24:22,963 --> 01:24:23,983
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I have a few thoughts.

1056
01:24:24,383 --> 01:24:26,203
[SPEAKER_01]: Prior to this, I was the assessor in Chelsea.

1057
01:24:26,223 --> 01:24:28,484
[SPEAKER_01]: They have a residential exemption, very familiar with it.

1058
01:24:29,884 --> 01:24:33,065
[SPEAKER_01]: The administrative burden it has on the office is quite high.

1059
01:24:34,005 --> 01:24:47,095
[SPEAKER_01]: In year one, we'd have to take about 8,000 applications in the city of Medford, and all of those have to be attached with that as their state income tax return so I can prove that they actually live in their Medford address and they're filing taxes from here.

1060
01:24:48,216 --> 01:24:52,079
[SPEAKER_01]: So it is a huge data security question with that.

1061
01:24:52,839 --> 01:24:56,342
[SPEAKER_01]: To process 8,000 applications, we would need another staff member or two.

1062
01:24:58,263 --> 01:25:03,469
[SPEAKER_01]: In addition, from a pure policy perspective, what it does is it shifts the burden within the residential class.

1063
01:25:04,149 --> 01:25:11,157
[SPEAKER_01]: So you have longtime Medford residents who own two and three families who would see an increase in their taxation.

1064
01:25:11,177 --> 01:25:13,199
[SPEAKER_01]: A lot of those are low-income elderly.

1065
01:25:13,239 --> 01:25:16,002
[SPEAKER_01]: We see them when they're filing for their personal exemptions.

1066
01:25:17,103 --> 01:25:18,424
[SPEAKER_01]: So it does benefit the

1067
01:25:19,045 --> 01:25:27,007
[SPEAKER_01]: condo owner generally, that it kind of shifts the burden from the three families and the two families or to the three families and the two families to the, you know, from the condo owner.

1068
01:25:27,047 --> 01:25:30,028
[SPEAKER_01]: So the condo owner is paying less in taxes.

1069
01:25:30,828 --> 01:25:32,628
[SPEAKER_20]: And the single families under the break even?

1070
01:25:32,648 --> 01:25:33,529
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

1071
01:25:33,629 --> 01:25:37,310
[SPEAKER_01]: And then you have to have the effects on your larger residential class.

1072
01:25:37,350 --> 01:25:42,611
[SPEAKER_01]: So like your larger apartment buildings or even your moderately sized apartment buildings that would see a significant tax increase.

1073
01:25:42,871 --> 01:25:46,372
[SPEAKER_20]: But is it generally fair to say you're shifting the burden from

1074
01:25:47,272 --> 01:25:50,654
[SPEAKER_20]: Lower valuation residential properties to higher valuation residential properties.

1075
01:25:50,974 --> 01:25:51,515
[SPEAKER_01]: Absolutely.

1076
01:25:51,695 --> 01:25:51,895
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

1077
01:25:52,255 --> 01:25:53,376
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

1078
01:25:54,697 --> 01:25:54,817
[SPEAKER_20]: Cool.

1079
01:25:54,837 --> 01:25:56,118
[SPEAKER_20]: I appreciate the quick analysis.

1080
01:25:56,138 --> 01:26:02,602
