1188
01:34:29,869 --> 01:34:34,310
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, I never passed the opportunity to make a comment on the police department, especially the budget.

1189
01:34:34,590 --> 01:34:38,792
[SPEAKER_17]: But I want to start by thanking you for allowing me to come speak to both the department speak on the budget.

1190
01:34:39,312 --> 01:34:44,234
[SPEAKER_17]: So fiscal 23 was a can another busy year for the Metro Police Department.

1191
01:34:44,574 --> 01:34:46,875
[SPEAKER_17]: We continue to increase our calls for service.

1192
01:34:47,495 --> 01:34:49,176
[SPEAKER_17]: I believe they were up to maybe 3% last year.

1193
01:34:50,536 --> 01:34:55,099
[SPEAKER_17]: About 9% of all our calls for service are 911 emergency calls, you know, hitting those buttons.

1194
01:34:55,119 --> 01:34:58,361
[SPEAKER_17]: And that's pretty significant for a city this size.

1195
01:34:59,862 --> 01:35:04,064
[SPEAKER_17]: Despite our efforts, the past year has seen an increase in crime.

1196
01:35:04,264 --> 01:35:11,829
[SPEAKER_17]: I think if you pay attention to the news and the way that society has been going, it won't be a surprise to you.

1197
01:35:11,889 --> 01:35:16,732
[SPEAKER_17]: I told you that a lot of those were both related to vandalism and assault based crime.

1198
01:35:16,892 --> 01:35:23,494
[SPEAKER_17]: All right, so domestic violence, unfortunately, we believe that this time has risen 5% in the last year.

1199
01:35:24,054 --> 01:35:27,356
[SPEAKER_17]: And of course, it's made the news, but we've had three homicides in the city.

1200
01:35:29,536 --> 01:35:42,921
[SPEAKER_17]: And when you report this stuff, I'm very confident to sit here before you and tell you that we have a very safe city, and in large part, because of the work of the women and men of our police department.

1201
01:35:44,821 --> 01:35:45,602
[SPEAKER_17]: The police department,

1202
01:35:47,513 --> 01:35:48,374
[SPEAKER_17]: A lot is asked of us.

1203
01:35:48,634 --> 01:35:54,580
[SPEAKER_17]: A lot of us is us every single year and there's a lot of changes that are produced or pushed upon the police department.

1204
01:35:55,140 --> 01:35:59,605
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm happy to say that we continue to be productive and responsible parts of this community.

1205
01:36:00,606 --> 01:36:03,889
[SPEAKER_17]: And we service probably close to 40,000 calls last year.

1206
01:36:07,232 --> 01:36:19,318
[SPEAKER_17]: So while we continue to see these increasing calls, we do, of course, continue to see an increase in calls that are related to mental health crisis and behavioral crisis.

1207
01:36:20,339 --> 01:36:23,721
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm happy to report that we still maintain a behavioral support unit.

1208
01:36:23,761 --> 01:36:25,722
[SPEAKER_17]: We have three full-time clinicians, even though

1209
01:36:27,122 --> 01:36:28,643
[SPEAKER_17]: One of them is out on a medical leave right now.

1210
01:36:29,023 --> 01:36:37,927
[SPEAKER_17]: Three full-time clinicians signed and working to a police department in the city is, it's not comparable to anywhere around here, you know, outside of Boston when they developed their plan.

1211
01:36:37,947 --> 01:36:41,208
[SPEAKER_17]: So we are well ahead of the game when it comes to those things.

1212
01:36:42,028 --> 01:36:51,870
[SPEAKER_17]: One of the major changes in that unit is we're running the clinicians in a co-response program, which means that when the police officers are out there in the day, we have a clinician in the police car with them.

1213
01:36:51,910 --> 01:36:54,411
[SPEAKER_17]: So they'll be first on scene first to make some evaluations.

1214
01:36:54,751 --> 01:37:00,092
[SPEAKER_17]: And a lot of times we know we're walking into a behavioral crisis issue or a mental health crisis issue.

1215
01:37:00,392 --> 01:37:05,033
[SPEAKER_17]: And the first contact is with that clinician rather than a police officer a lot of those times.

1216
01:37:05,514 --> 01:37:08,234
[SPEAKER_17]: So we're having great success when it comes to that.

1217
01:37:08,654 --> 01:37:11,135
[SPEAKER_17]: And we're going to continue to kind of push in that direction.

1218
01:37:13,916 --> 01:37:19,119
[SPEAKER_17]: I never take, miss the opportunity to thank, as I started to say, the men and women of our police department.

1219
01:37:19,819 --> 01:37:26,123
[SPEAKER_17]: And that includes the uniformed personnel, public safety dispatchers, and the civilian teams.

1220
01:37:26,143 --> 01:37:31,646
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, each year more is asked of us and they respond in very impressive ways.

1221
01:37:33,100 --> 01:37:38,221
[SPEAKER_17]: I can easily stand here and say that our police department is among the very best in the state of Massachusetts.

1222
01:37:38,621 --> 01:37:40,021
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm confident in that statement.

1223
01:37:41,802 --> 01:37:51,863
[SPEAKER_17]: I know a lot of times I have to stand up here and represent them, but I think they represent us every single day in very, very positive ways, especially doing a tough job.

1224
01:37:53,043 --> 01:38:01,185
[SPEAKER_17]: The job of police officers and public safety dispatchers, it's critical to the security and the safety each of us feel in this community.

1225
01:38:03,172 --> 01:38:04,955
[SPEAKER_17]: No, they're positive contributors.

1226
01:38:04,975 --> 01:38:05,956
[SPEAKER_17]: They're not just employees.

1227
01:38:06,156 --> 01:38:06,717
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't look at them.

1228
01:38:06,737 --> 01:38:13,306
[SPEAKER_17]: They're positive contributors to our city and they help create that reputation that Medford has.

1229
01:38:13,326 --> 01:38:17,172
[SPEAKER_17]: That being said, we continue to evaluate.

1230
01:38:19,028 --> 01:38:22,489
[SPEAKER_17]: where we are going both as an organization and a community partnership.

1231
01:38:23,429 --> 01:38:28,410
[SPEAKER_17]: And to that end, I'm happy to report that last year it was already talked about.

1232
01:38:28,430 --> 01:38:29,410
[SPEAKER_17]: We had the national night out.

1233
01:38:29,430 --> 01:38:32,150
[SPEAKER_17]: It was one of the largest community events the police department has put on.

1234
01:38:33,551 --> 01:38:38,412
[SPEAKER_17]: I always want to sit here and tell you that it wasn't the administration of the police department that put that on.

1235
01:38:38,432 --> 01:38:40,292
[SPEAKER_17]: That was the police officers themselves, right?

1236
01:38:40,312 --> 01:38:45,633
[SPEAKER_17]: So I've tasked the police officers over the last couple of years to don't be driven by the chief of police saying,

1237
01:38:46,714 --> 01:38:50,681
[SPEAKER_17]: get involved with the community, get involved with the community yourselves, and I'll support those endeavors.

1238
01:38:51,422 --> 01:38:55,731
[SPEAKER_17]: And National Night Out last August was one of the best events that we have run in my career.

1239
01:38:57,717 --> 01:39:04,778
[SPEAKER_17]: And the success of that has led to the police department, those same community engagement officers applied for a grant with the Cummings grant.

1240
01:39:04,858 --> 01:39:11,460
[SPEAKER_17]: And we were just recently awarded $100,000 over three years to continue community engagement through the Cummings Foundation.

1241
01:39:11,540 --> 01:39:13,600
[SPEAKER_17]: I can't be any happier for my police officers.

1242
01:39:13,640 --> 01:39:14,800
[SPEAKER_17]: It was driven by them.

1243
01:39:15,200 --> 01:39:21,542
[SPEAKER_17]: And I can't be any more grateful for the Cummings group for supporting our endeavor of community engagement.

1244
01:39:24,773 --> 01:39:27,534
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, I said it before, it's not just police officers.

1245
01:39:27,894 --> 01:39:30,655
[SPEAKER_17]: I do want to thank all of my civilian employees.

1246
01:39:31,595 --> 01:39:37,877
[SPEAKER_17]: Public safety dispatchers continue to evolve and continue to do a great job under stressful conditions and increasing call amounts.

1247
01:39:38,437 --> 01:39:46,780
[SPEAKER_17]: I will always pass up the, never pass up the opportunity to thank my secretary, Alva, going on 64 years now working as an employee of the police department.

1248
01:39:47,600 --> 01:39:52,002
[SPEAKER_17]: Linda Collazo, who is always here and keeping me in line when it comes to, you know, my budget numbers.

1249
01:39:52,702 --> 01:39:56,625
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, she follows me here just to make sure I don't say anything that gets me in trouble.

1250
01:39:57,526 --> 01:39:59,687
[SPEAKER_17]: And finally, to Diane Riley.

1251
01:40:00,548 --> 01:40:07,293
[SPEAKER_17]: Diane has worked in the records office, and today is her very last day, and she's retired, so I just want to thank her for all her years of service.

1252
01:40:08,373 --> 01:40:13,817
[SPEAKER_17]: She's very important to me and running this police department, and I thank her wholeheartedly for everything that she has done for us.

1253
01:40:13,837 --> 01:40:17,580
[SPEAKER_17]: So I hope you're watching, Diane, because we can meet up with her later on.

1254
01:40:19,321 --> 01:40:22,803
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, we have a lot of partners in the police department, we do not do this alone.

1255
01:40:22,823 --> 01:40:25,805
[SPEAKER_17]: So I clearly want to thank the mayor and her office for her support.

1256
01:40:26,606 --> 01:40:33,110
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not easy to run a police department and the support you receive from the team in the city of Medford is invaluable.

1257
01:40:33,851 --> 01:40:40,135
[SPEAKER_17]: We work closely with the fire department, they create partners for us, Armstrong Ambulance, even though private entity is very good for us.

1258
01:40:40,595 --> 01:40:43,497
[SPEAKER_17]: But I have traffic supervisors every day working hard to get out there

1259
01:40:44,017 --> 01:40:47,299
[SPEAKER_17]: And last but not least, the DPW, and especially Mike Wentzel's team, right?

1260
01:40:47,399 --> 01:40:52,822
[SPEAKER_17]: He keeps my cruises and my maintenance in line, and we're not for want of the ball when it comes to that sort of thing.

1261
01:40:56,286 --> 01:40:58,468
[SPEAKER_17]: What you two expect to see in this next fiscal year?

1262
01:40:59,028 --> 01:41:04,652
[SPEAKER_17]: By mid-June, we will finally be out with our body-worn cameras and public.

1263
01:41:04,932 --> 01:41:06,753
[SPEAKER_17]: We're very close with that final policy.

1264
01:41:07,594 --> 01:41:11,336
[SPEAKER_17]: I think my last meeting with the union will be this coming week.

1265
01:41:11,436 --> 01:41:12,237
[SPEAKER_17]: The policy will be

1266
01:41:14,058 --> 01:41:24,385
[SPEAKER_17]: we're going to be reviewing that policy with the mayor, and then I'll present to the council and go over that pursuit policy.

1267
01:41:24,746 --> 01:41:26,807
[SPEAKER_17]: And then there'll be some public outreach that goes with that, right?

1268
01:41:26,827 --> 01:41:35,493
[SPEAKER_17]: So we don't want to just start showing up, and I know it's new for us, and it's going to be new for the public, but it will be valuable and important for this community to take that next step

1269
01:41:54,217 --> 01:41:57,459
[SPEAKER_17]: see if I had anything else I wanted to add as far as the policy.

1270
01:41:57,479 --> 01:41:59,881
[SPEAKER_17]: So I think that's it for sort of highlights.

1271
01:41:59,941 --> 01:42:05,524
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, it's been a busy year for us, but I'm open and willing to listen to any questions and answer.

1272
01:42:09,967 --> 01:42:10,487
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Chief.

1273
01:42:10,588 --> 01:42:11,668
[SPEAKER_08]: Go to Councilor Scarpalli.

1274
01:42:12,249 --> 01:42:13,569
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Madam President.

