1537
02:03:21,870 --> 02:03:23,010
[SPEAKER_17]: It's all right.

1538
02:03:23,390 --> 02:03:34,174
[SPEAKER_20]: No, and you know, that's the reason I'm asking, especially on these big buckets for one of the things we're looking at is an ordinance to say, how can we actually assess what our needs are in each department?

1539
02:03:34,634 --> 02:03:45,257
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think one of those things that's going to have to eventually go and inform that is, you know, measuring success, if we have needs, what are we trying to fix with those needs or improve with those needs?

1540
02:03:45,337 --> 02:03:45,397
[SPEAKER_20]: And

1541
02:03:46,127 --> 02:03:59,475
[SPEAKER_20]: So I'm trying to get a handle and a feel on from the folks, and I'm sure you have thoughts, I'm sure people in your department have thoughts, and maybe in the future we could hear some of that and report back too, but it's up to you.

1542
02:03:59,535 --> 02:04:01,636
[SPEAKER_17]: It's a valuable question and something we should be sort of

1543
02:04:01,696 --> 02:04:02,297
[SPEAKER_17]: look at that.

1544
02:04:02,397 --> 02:04:03,859
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't know that the answer will be that easy.

1545
02:04:03,899 --> 02:04:07,663
[SPEAKER_17]: As a police professional, I kind of really like the question.

1546
02:04:07,703 --> 02:04:09,225
[SPEAKER_17]: I'll be thinking about that one for a little while.

1547
02:04:10,126 --> 02:04:13,811
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not that we don't ask ourselves this command stuff every day, like, hey, what are we doing right?

1548
02:04:13,831 --> 02:04:14,572
[SPEAKER_17]: What are we doing wrong?

1549
02:04:14,592 --> 02:04:18,156
[SPEAKER_17]: But how do you put that in a metric that you can measure it?

1550
02:04:18,176 --> 02:04:18,597
[SPEAKER_20]: Exactly.

1551
02:04:18,977 --> 02:04:20,719
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's really the question I'm trying to get at is,

1552
02:04:21,605 --> 02:04:25,267
[SPEAKER_20]: you probably have a really good intuitive feel for it, having been doing something for a long time.

1553
02:04:25,868 --> 02:04:28,129
[SPEAKER_20]: What's a number that maybe reflects your intuition?

1554
02:04:28,149 --> 02:04:29,570
[SPEAKER_20]: That's not an easy question to answer.

1555
02:04:29,610 --> 02:04:30,811
[SPEAKER_20]: So, understood.

1556
02:04:31,432 --> 02:04:34,394
[SPEAKER_20]: Last question, just a little bit about the Traffic Commission.

1557
02:04:34,454 --> 02:04:36,255
[SPEAKER_20]: I know Councillor Collins asked about that.

1558
02:04:39,877 --> 02:04:42,399
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know that I'm going to win any popularity points for what I'm about to say.

1559
02:04:44,296 --> 02:04:44,376
[SPEAKER_20]: that.

1560
02:04:44,396 --> 02:04:47,038
[SPEAKER_20]: Sometimes certainly not from Councilor Knight.

1561
02:04:47,979 --> 02:04:49,760
[SPEAKER_20]: Sometimes there are, you know.

1562
02:04:50,701 --> 02:04:59,547
[SPEAKER_20]: Traffic design interventions that the city wants to do that they feel will make situations on our streets significantly safer and to avoid injuries and fatalities.

1563
02:04:59,607 --> 02:05:00,008
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm really.

1564
02:05:00,948 --> 02:05:04,431
[SPEAKER_20]: Super disappointed to hear that there was a traffic fatality this weekend.

1565
02:05:04,451 --> 02:05:05,292
[SPEAKER_20]: I hadn't heard that

1566
02:05:13,392 --> 02:05:24,419
[SPEAKER_20]: people who, um, you know, are against those safety interventions for reasons of personal convenience or work, sometimes commercial convenience.

1567
02:05:25,480 --> 02:05:31,004
[SPEAKER_20]: Um, and sometimes the Traffic Commission adjusts plans that

1568
02:05:32,109 --> 02:05:40,611
[SPEAKER_20]: to prioritize convenience over the absolute best idea of safety, at least based on the design plans that are presented to the traffic commission.

1569
02:05:41,351 --> 02:05:45,012
[SPEAKER_20]: If you don't accept that characterization, I understand, but that's how I interpret it sometimes.

1570
02:05:45,032 --> 02:05:46,373
[SPEAKER_20]: And I understand this difficult job.

1571
02:05:46,453 --> 02:05:51,174
[SPEAKER_20]: I know you're balancing interests and I know pretty well what that looks like sometimes.

1572
02:05:51,254 --> 02:05:54,175
[SPEAKER_20]: And we've been in rooms doing it together sometimes.

1573
02:05:55,015 --> 02:05:57,876
[SPEAKER_20]: What can we do to make the traffic commission

1574
02:06:00,993 --> 02:06:11,071
[SPEAKER_20]: What can we do to try to prioritize leaning in that direction of safety more, or is there anything you know, I don't know exactly what I'm asking but I think you get where I'm going with it.

1575
02:06:14,332 --> 02:06:25,221
[SPEAKER_20]: most of the time we're leaning in that direction of making the streets and roads safer by design changes rather than necessarily prioritizing convenience of certain private individuals on the streets.

1576
02:06:26,102 --> 02:06:30,966
[SPEAKER_17]: So I think I have a clear message of what you're trying to send and I will say that

1577
02:06:32,207 --> 02:06:34,688
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, the traffic commission is a regulatory body, right?

1578
02:06:34,748 --> 02:06:38,390
[SPEAKER_17]: And so we don't design streets, we don't design plants.

1579
02:06:38,570 --> 02:06:44,633
[SPEAKER_17]: That's, you know, as a police chief, I'm not a, you know, traffic engineer, and I know I don't have that expertise.

1580
02:06:44,693 --> 02:06:51,697
[SPEAKER_17]: And nor do the, you know, the other members who sit upon that traffic commission, we rely heavily on our traffic engineering,

1581
02:06:52,357 --> 02:06:54,718
[SPEAKER_17]: Director Blake does an outstanding job.

1582
02:06:55,338 --> 02:07:03,942
[SPEAKER_17]: And over the years, there are things that have demanded upon us of the Traffic Commission where Director Blake will say, no, this is a safety issue.

1583
02:07:03,982 --> 02:07:05,883
[SPEAKER_17]: We can't do X, Y, Z, or we can't do everything.

1584
02:07:05,943 --> 02:07:14,066
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think it's probably about a 99.9% time that we abide by what the engineer tells us because it is a matter of safety.

1585
02:07:15,687 --> 02:07:17,667
[SPEAKER_17]: The Traffic Commission is an offshoot of the police department.

1586
02:07:17,687 --> 02:07:18,908
[SPEAKER_17]: It is about public safety.

1587
02:07:19,980 --> 02:07:32,788
[SPEAKER_17]: One of the things that goes hand in hand, though, sometimes is when, you know, if you push for a public safety initiative, and it will take away like, I mean, the direct issue with the direct comments like vast amount of parking, right?

1588
02:07:34,869 --> 02:07:41,754
[SPEAKER_17]: It becomes a struggle for a regulatory body to sit there and say, by design, we want to take away 50 parking spots.

1589
02:07:43,036 --> 02:07:46,137
[SPEAKER_17]: doesn't mean you don't support the safety initiative, but how do you do that in one week?

1590
02:07:46,438 --> 02:07:48,559
[SPEAKER_17]: How do you just tell people you don't have any place to park?

1591
02:07:48,659 --> 02:07:55,122
[SPEAKER_17]: And that becomes, it's just such a tough, it's a conundrum that nobody really has a solution to, right?

1592
02:07:55,142 --> 02:07:59,404
[SPEAKER_17]: Because we have excessive amounts of vehicles registered to the city of Medford and not at a park.

1593
02:08:00,004 --> 02:08:05,146
[SPEAKER_17]: We continue to see development that comes into the city without requirements for them to provide parking for them.

1594
02:08:05,887 --> 02:08:10,029
[SPEAKER_17]: And digging yourself into a hole is a traffic commission, right?

1595
02:08:10,049 --> 02:08:12,490
[SPEAKER_17]: Because if you make a decision,

1596
02:08:14,028 --> 02:08:16,530
[SPEAKER_17]: We made decisions that we think are safe based on the engineers.

1597
02:08:17,251 --> 02:08:19,533
[SPEAKER_17]: It wasn't what everybody wanted, and I understand that.

1598
02:08:21,254 --> 02:08:26,559
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it was a valuable compromise because in the engineer side, they supported it too, and that's good enough for me.

1599
02:08:26,699 --> 02:08:27,920
[SPEAKER_17]: Can we have a clarification, Madam President?

1600
02:08:28,981 --> 02:08:30,462
[SPEAKER_17]: Can someone fill me in on what we're talking about here?

1601
02:08:31,503 --> 02:08:33,465
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm not talking about a specific proposal.

1602
02:08:33,505 --> 02:08:34,986
[SPEAKER_20]: I think you're referencing Winthrop Street.

1603
02:08:35,186 --> 02:08:38,189
[SPEAKER_17]: Yep, because it's the perfect example of what came up.

1604
02:08:38,269 --> 02:08:40,051
[SPEAKER_17]: It's the Winthrop Street idea, right, and the traffic.

1605
02:08:40,580 --> 02:08:46,562
[SPEAKER_17]: But as soon as we take it away, there's this new phenomenon in the city of Medford where I don't have parking, the city has to provide it for me.

1606
02:08:47,082 --> 02:08:48,583
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't know that we can do that all the time.

1607
02:08:49,943 --> 02:08:51,784
[SPEAKER_17]: And so it's a problem.

1608
02:08:51,824 --> 02:08:57,946
[SPEAKER_17]: But I will say this, the Traffic Commission has, in my four and a half years, worked for a safer community.

1609
02:08:59,006 --> 02:09:00,627
[SPEAKER_17]: But we have never made everyone happy.

1610
02:09:00,927 --> 02:09:03,588
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, and I know we're not gonna make everybody happy.

1611
02:09:03,628 --> 02:09:07,129
[SPEAKER_20]: And Winthrop Street was huge, came here, we talked about it.

1612
02:09:07,449 --> 02:09:09,030
[SPEAKER_20]: You guys had a big discussion on it.

1613
02:09:10,047 --> 02:09:14,551
[SPEAKER_20]: You know, I think even I use the phrase reasonable accommodation and the traffic commission meeting for that one.

1614
02:09:15,472 --> 02:09:22,438
[SPEAKER_20]: I think where I'm more targeting is sometimes you'll get something that comes down from traffic commission from traffic engineer Blake.

1615
02:09:23,319 --> 02:09:31,346
[SPEAKER_20]: Say, let's take Auburn and North Street we had a committee of the whole on that almost two years ago, and director Blake proposed some

1616
02:09:32,627 --> 02:09:46,161
[SPEAKER_20]: What I thought were reasonable changes to address people driving down streets one way streets the wrong way and shortening very very long crosswalks at a dangerous intersection and putting in a little bit more signage comes on the agenda, Director Blake thinks it's a good idea.

1617
02:09:46,856 --> 02:09:51,598
[SPEAKER_20]: one person who abuts the project says they don't like it and it's been on the table for two years.

1618
02:09:51,998 --> 02:09:54,359
[SPEAKER_20]: That's the kind of thing that I'm trying to avoid.

1619
02:09:54,740 --> 02:10:04,604
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not so sure it's still on the table, but I'll follow up with you, but I have a petition of like 100 plus people who came out against that and plans.

1620
02:10:08,025 --> 02:10:18,830
[SPEAKER_17]: for multitude of reasons, it just gets to be an issue of, at this point in time, the traffic commission has to send all those concerns back to engineer, like, yeah, I keep going back to this that we do not design the changes, right?

1621
02:10:19,010 --> 02:10:20,471
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't know.

1622
02:10:20,591 --> 02:10:24,073
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, I got a great understanding of it all, because I'm a police officer, but

1623
02:10:24,433 --> 02:10:31,799
[SPEAKER_17]: We don't do it we don't do it every little thing has this national highway transportation that you have to kind of follow these leads and what you're going to write I know we put a good plan together.

1624
02:10:32,319 --> 02:10:37,504
[SPEAKER_17]: But there were community needs that people started objecting and said what about this and this I think they have to be addressed.

1625
02:10:37,584 --> 02:10:44,369
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's fair and that I respect that's the process we had 40 people at a committee the whole 38 of them love the idea that was proposed.

1626
02:10:45,170 --> 02:10:48,492
[SPEAKER_20]: And my concern is less so that we, you know, we can try to balance the interest there.

1627
02:10:49,293 --> 02:10:53,498
[SPEAKER_20]: but that it doesn't get lost for a year, two years down the road.

1628
02:10:53,538 --> 02:11:01,928
[SPEAKER_20]: That's the piece where I'm like, I understand there's people who aren't going to like changes and I understand trying to have a process where we try to understand those concerns and incorporate them.

1629
02:11:02,629 --> 02:11:08,516
[SPEAKER_20]: I just don't like the piece where sometimes it's like the concerns come up, it has to go back to engineering and then it just kind of falls off the radar.

1630
02:11:09,356 --> 02:11:13,297
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'll add an additional thing that we've been thinking about, or as commissioner, I've been thinking about also.

1631
02:11:13,337 --> 02:11:21,739
[SPEAKER_17]: So you get a proposal like that, we'll just use it as somewhat of an example where, okay, we need to redesign this whole intersection and everything.

1632
02:11:22,559 --> 02:11:26,320
[SPEAKER_17]: Director Blake can say, ah, do this, this and this, draw it up, and the traffic commission can say, sure.

1633
02:11:26,940 --> 02:11:29,760
[SPEAKER_17]: And we just put like a set of lights, it's almost a million dollars.

1634
02:11:30,120 --> 02:11:37,142
[SPEAKER_17]: And you put like a one to $2 million burden on the city, and I don't know that that is necessarily what the traffic commission's,

1635
02:11:37,962 --> 02:11:46,548
[SPEAKER_17]: purposes for right to get regulatory body, it all gets decided, it all gets designed, we vote that you can enforce that crosswalk, you can enforce that trip, that set of lights.

1636
02:11:47,148 --> 02:11:56,074
[SPEAKER_17]: I think over time, people have looked at the traffic commission as being the end all is to say, you design it, you tell us what to do here, we want this, you approve it, it gets done.

1637
02:11:56,094 --> 02:11:57,896
[SPEAKER_17]: A lot goes into it, right?

1638
02:11:58,016 --> 02:11:59,537
[SPEAKER_17]: A lot of money to change.

1639
02:11:59,597 --> 02:12:00,317
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, sure.

1640
02:12:00,558 --> 02:12:03,480
[SPEAKER_20]: So it's, it's, this one was painting signs, so.

1641
02:12:04,260 --> 02:12:07,722
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, I think science costs money, which we'll be talking about afterwards, right?

1642
02:12:07,882 --> 02:12:08,563
[SPEAKER_20]: Not a million bucks.

1643
02:12:08,603 --> 02:12:16,307
[SPEAKER_20]: But, you know, for me, my flip side of it is, if you think it's the safest interventions, I think that's helpful for us to know.

1644
02:12:16,948 --> 02:12:20,530
[SPEAKER_20]: Because maybe we can't afford it today, but maybe we need it.

1645
02:12:20,610 --> 02:12:24,032
[SPEAKER_20]: How can we make a plan to afford it in two years, five years down the road.

1646
02:12:24,752 --> 02:12:32,237
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's the piece of it like, and it's not a criticism of you, although you are the chair of the traffic commission, I know that you don't design the roads and you're not the only person who votes on it.

1647
02:12:34,352 --> 02:12:44,334
[SPEAKER_20]: you know, I think in Medford, we've gotten in this habit of things, we don't analyze what our actual end goal need is.

1648
02:12:44,654 --> 02:12:49,355
[SPEAKER_20]: And that means that we kind of never get there because we don't know where we're trying to get to.

1649
02:12:49,535 --> 02:12:50,315
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's my thing.

1650
02:12:50,355 --> 02:12:57,216
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that's happening with some of these ideas and projects and different places where, you know, I like what we're doing at Maine and South.

1651
02:12:57,276 --> 02:13:00,877
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that new intervention with the curbing is great, you know,

1652
02:13:01,817 --> 02:13:06,119
[SPEAKER_20]: But our goal three years ago was a full set of lights and reconfiguring the whole thing.

1653
02:13:06,199 --> 02:13:07,960
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's still coming, right?

1654
02:13:08,020 --> 02:13:09,941
[SPEAKER_17]: And again, that's the state, the state decided.

1655
02:13:10,001 --> 02:13:13,362
[SPEAKER_17]: No, I guess it even sort of surprised me that they wanted to extend that island up.

1656
02:13:13,422 --> 02:13:15,323
[SPEAKER_20]: And I'm like, yeah, and I get that.

1657
02:13:15,543 --> 02:13:22,867
[SPEAKER_20]: And I know that that one's multi-jurisdictional, but I think there's just a few examples I could point to where there are places where we've all generally agreed that we could do better.

1658
02:13:23,527 --> 02:13:28,249
[SPEAKER_20]: We get a little caught up in the specifics and then the process there kind of falls through a gap and hole in the process.

1659
02:13:28,309 --> 02:13:29,890
[SPEAKER_20]: And we don't really get where we wanted to go.

1660
02:13:30,410 --> 02:13:44,721
[SPEAKER_17]: So to a large extent, I believe I agree with what you stated on like that we need a better or at least a holistic approach to a lot of things we're doing as far as it's not just urban design, but traffic is a large part of all that and to go forward and we can all participate.

1661
02:13:46,142 --> 02:13:49,545
[SPEAKER_17]: It's, you know, the traffic commission is the hottest part time job I've had.

1662
02:13:49,645 --> 02:13:50,685
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, I can imagine.

1663
02:13:50,906 --> 02:13:51,686
[SPEAKER_20]: I've seen that.

1664
02:13:52,687 --> 02:13:57,551
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm glad it's not not this council another one for this council to have a knockdown drag out about.

1665
02:13:57,911 --> 02:13:58,071
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

1666
02:14:00,235 --> 02:14:02,937
[SPEAKER_17]: It's interesting, but all good stuff that we constantly.

1667
02:14:02,997 --> 02:14:07,620
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm glad that we're consistently looking at the rules and the roles of the Traffic Commission.

1668
02:14:07,660 --> 02:14:11,002
[SPEAKER_17]: We meet regularly on this, and you'll see some changes coming up.

1669
02:14:11,523 --> 02:14:16,406
[SPEAKER_17]: The question is when those changes will come about, as fast as we can make them happen, but there's a lot of work that needs to go into it.

1670
02:14:16,566 --> 02:14:25,512
[SPEAKER_20]: And on the holistic piece and the process piece, if there's ways that this council can have any sort of roll-by ordinance that assists you, I think we are all willing and ready to do that.

1671
02:14:26,012 --> 02:14:26,393
[SPEAKER_20]: Understood.

1672
02:14:26,513 --> 02:14:26,813
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

1673
02:14:26,913 --> 02:14:27,233
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

1674
02:14:27,293 --> 02:14:27,573
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm good.

1675
02:14:27,633 --> 02:14:28,354
[SPEAKER_20]: Thanks, Madam President.

1676
02:14:28,614 --> 02:14:28,874
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1677
02:14:34,331 --> 02:14:49,459
[SPEAKER_02]: I want to thank you for the work you've done in a short period of time to bring us our police department up to a modern department that addresses all the needs of the community.

1678
02:14:49,479 --> 02:14:50,660
[SPEAKER_02]: So thank you for that.

1679
02:14:54,663 --> 02:14:55,284
[SPEAKER_02]: an open office.

1680
02:14:55,584 --> 02:15:02,129
[SPEAKER_02]: So as I look around the city, now I see, I think, I think we probably have the youngest police department in the area.

1681
02:15:02,169 --> 02:15:05,592
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, it kind of makes me feel old.

1682
02:15:05,812 --> 02:15:12,437
[SPEAKER_02]: I think everybody, when everyone's like around 20 years old, it looks like, how many retirees here do you have coming up?

1683
02:15:13,697 --> 02:15:15,258
[SPEAKER_17]: So that was just asked to me the other day.

1684
02:15:15,278 --> 02:15:17,000
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't think we have any scheduled.

1685
02:15:17,260 --> 02:15:19,082
[SPEAKER_17]: So 65 years old, we have to retire.

1686
02:15:19,482 --> 02:15:21,503
[SPEAKER_17]: So it's a mandatory retirement of police officers.

1687
02:15:21,604 --> 02:15:23,585
[SPEAKER_17]: And we look at those as a benchmark.

1688
02:15:23,605 --> 02:15:27,568
[SPEAKER_17]: And I don't think we have one coming up for related to that in the next two years.

1689
02:15:27,708 --> 02:15:28,789
[SPEAKER_17]: So we're good for a few years.

1690
02:15:28,990 --> 02:15:30,271
[SPEAKER_17]: Good for a few years.

1691
02:15:30,291 --> 02:15:32,672
[SPEAKER_17]: Do I anticipate we may lose three to retirement?

1692
02:15:32,713 --> 02:15:34,154
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, anyone can leave at any time.

1693
02:15:34,234 --> 02:15:35,675
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm guessing a number could be.

1694
02:15:35,735 --> 02:15:38,817
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think, I think they asked about

1695
02:15:39,638 --> 02:15:40,659
[SPEAKER_17]: officers in the academy?

1696
02:15:41,159 --> 02:15:50,326
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes again we're going through the process right now we're pushing it along we have uh we're we're slated to try to put six in the academy by July 17th I think today.

1697
02:15:50,406 --> 02:15:55,850
[SPEAKER_02]: So by next year we'll we'll uh have a we'll we'll be up to a better number than 73 patrolmen?

1698
02:15:56,290 --> 02:15:59,112
[SPEAKER_02]: Uh we we we we should be yes.

1699
02:15:59,132 --> 02:16:00,473
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay um

1700
02:16:04,328 --> 02:16:05,088
[SPEAKER_02]: The police station?

1701
02:16:05,389 --> 02:16:05,569
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes.

1702
02:16:06,349 --> 02:16:10,832
[SPEAKER_02]: Are we funding it properly for management and maintenance?

1703
02:16:11,192 --> 02:16:16,315
[SPEAKER_02]: I know, I know that's been a weak point of the city for many, many years, you know, we don't, we don't take care of our property.

1704
02:16:16,876 --> 02:16:18,477
[SPEAKER_02]: Are we spending enough money?

1705
02:16:18,717 --> 02:16:20,118
[SPEAKER_17]: We have a cleaning crew that's in there.

1706
02:16:20,178 --> 02:16:20,698
[SPEAKER_17]: It's working.

1707
02:16:20,978 --> 02:16:21,859
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't have any issues.

1708
02:16:21,879 --> 02:16:28,203
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, all VG who's it was the facilities maintenance guy is constantly over in our police department working.

1709
02:16:29,123 --> 02:16:34,646
[SPEAKER_17]: We've, you know, a new building, we had some growing pains, especially with a few different areas, they're all kind of working through and resolved itself.

1710
02:16:34,986 --> 02:16:39,128
[SPEAKER_17]: It takes a long time to get an HVAC system balanced in a new building, and we may have, you know.

1711
02:16:39,368 --> 02:16:44,130
[SPEAKER_02]: So we're spending enough money to keep the building up to its proper standards?

1712
02:16:44,230 --> 02:16:54,135
[SPEAKER_17]: To the best that I can tell, because even some of those that don't fall into my, you know, under my budget, but I can't be happy with what's going on with the building right now.

1713
02:16:54,735 --> 02:16:56,277
[SPEAKER_02]: You can get HVAC outs in this building.

1714
02:16:56,417 --> 02:16:58,199
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, it's everywhere.

1715
02:16:58,480 --> 02:17:07,411
[SPEAKER_02]: Question I ask every year, and I know you don't want to answer it, and I know you struggle to fill details every day.

1716
02:17:08,813 --> 02:17:10,575
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there a plan to bring the retirees on?

1717
02:17:11,325 --> 02:17:13,887
[SPEAKER_02]: to lessen the burden on you?

1718
02:17:14,507 --> 02:17:15,468
[SPEAKER_17]: There's always a plan.

1719
02:17:15,668 --> 02:17:20,551
[SPEAKER_17]: It really is about negotiations with both unions when it comes down to this.

1720
02:17:20,952 --> 02:17:23,333
[SPEAKER_17]: And we've done some considerable work on this.

1721
02:17:23,353 --> 02:17:24,194
[SPEAKER_02]: Many cities have them.

1722
02:17:24,814 --> 02:17:26,936
[SPEAKER_02]: They allow them to work for a few years after they retire.

1723
02:17:27,456 --> 02:17:32,419
[SPEAKER_02]: And I drive by and I see work projects unmanned with no detail on them.

1724
02:17:32,560 --> 02:17:35,522
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, it is a problem.

1725
02:17:35,602 --> 02:17:36,582
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, what's happening is

1726
02:17:38,237 --> 02:17:47,867
[SPEAKER_17]: you know, I'm not gonna say we're down significantly in police officers, but we are down significantly in police officers who certainly have an interest in working some extra time, right, you know, but

1727
02:17:49,223 --> 02:18:06,053
[SPEAKER_17]: those, the kind of quandary we're having a little bit with police officers, retired police officers working is that they have to meet all, if you're gonna wear this uniform as a police officer, just do a road job as a retiree, you have to meet all the standards of post requirement and all the training, that's a burden on the police departments also.

1728
02:18:06,073 --> 02:18:09,516
[SPEAKER_17]: So we're trying to find ways around that and get some assistance to help with that.

1729
02:18:09,716 --> 02:18:11,397
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

1730
02:18:11,477 --> 02:18:12,057
[SPEAKER_02]: Two more questions.

1731
02:18:13,298 --> 02:18:16,200
[SPEAKER_02]: How many police union contracts are not settled yet?

1732
02:18:17,476 --> 02:18:20,478
[SPEAKER_02]: We have two police units and they're both open.

1733
02:18:20,518 --> 02:18:22,459
[SPEAKER_02]: They're not settled yet, they're open still?

1734
02:18:22,599 --> 02:18:23,179
[SPEAKER_02]: They're open, yes.

1735
02:18:24,700 --> 02:18:29,423
[SPEAKER_02]: And my last question, it seems like your budget is level funded.

1736
02:18:30,097 --> 02:18:33,580
[SPEAKER_02]: Were there any needs that weren't addressed in here that you would like to see?

1737
02:18:33,660 --> 02:18:33,901
[SPEAKER_02]: Nothing?

1738
02:18:34,341 --> 02:18:38,425
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of the things I shifted around, you know, in response to expense things.

1739
02:18:38,845 --> 02:18:40,066
[SPEAKER_17]: No wish list?

1740
02:18:40,727 --> 02:18:42,909
[SPEAKER_17]: A wish list is different than budget needs.

1741
02:18:43,029 --> 02:18:44,250
[SPEAKER_17]: I get asked that question all the time.

1742
02:18:44,290 --> 02:18:46,632
[SPEAKER_17]: I got a huge wish list, but it's a totally different question.

1743
02:18:50,536 --> 02:18:50,916
[SPEAKER_17]: that the

1744
02:19:14,549 --> 02:19:16,730
[SPEAKER_17]: Is Alva going to be there longer than you for another chief?

1745
02:19:17,330 --> 02:19:20,011
[SPEAKER_17]: I have already told Alva she will have another chief.

1746
02:19:20,031 --> 02:19:21,731
[SPEAKER_02]: You're the third chief.

1747
02:19:22,572 --> 02:19:23,412
[SPEAKER_17]: She's healthy as a horse.

1748
02:19:23,512 --> 02:19:26,193
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't want to talk about it.

1749
02:19:26,213 --> 02:19:27,053
[SPEAKER_17]: She'll leave tomorrow.

1750
02:19:27,073 --> 02:19:27,873
[SPEAKER_17]: God bless Alva.

1751
02:19:28,773 --> 02:19:29,214
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Chief.

1752
02:19:29,574 --> 02:19:29,934
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1753
02:19:29,954 --> 02:19:30,714
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

1754
02:19:30,874 --> 02:19:33,015
[SPEAKER_08]: Any other questions from the council?

1755
02:19:34,416 --> 02:19:40,218
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, I know we had talked about this in person and you mentioned the education component of around traffic.

1756
02:19:40,338 --> 02:19:51,621
[SPEAKER_08]: Is there any different approach to traffic enforcement or, or hours just in consideration of increase in traffic deaths, pedestrian deaths nationwide at the state level?

1757
02:19:52,191 --> 02:20:04,858
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, I mean, so the good thing is, is, you know, when we get these new offices, we can, you know, move some people around, we can increase our traffic, and we've maintained a traffic unit separate from patrol for many, many years.

1758
02:20:04,918 --> 02:20:07,779
