2114
02:45:19,297 --> 02:45:28,844
[SPEAKER_14]: And I know that she's worked with all these businesses to get them, and Victor too, but to get them all these resources, advice, advising,

2115
02:45:30,424 --> 02:45:35,626
[SPEAKER_14]: helping them with data, just smart business strategy.

2116
02:45:36,226 --> 02:45:42,008
[SPEAKER_14]: And a lot of residents, they always ask, when is the economic development coming to Medford?

2117
02:45:42,028 --> 02:45:44,249
[SPEAKER_14]: But there's already a lot of work being done.

2118
02:45:44,729 --> 02:45:47,290
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think this is also a good time to showcase that.

2119
02:45:47,330 --> 02:45:55,353
[SPEAKER_14]: And of course, we're all excited for more development to come, but there's a lot of good foundational work that's being done right now that I think should be highlighted as well.

2120
02:45:55,733 --> 02:45:59,935
[SPEAKER_03]: We do have a small business guide and PDF on the website for businesses to get started.

2121
02:46:00,435 --> 02:46:08,399
[SPEAKER_03]: And there is a nonprofit that will help people with business plans and how to run a small business that we connected the library to.

2122
02:46:08,519 --> 02:46:10,980
[SPEAKER_03]: So it's on the library resources to connect to that.

2123
02:46:11,040 --> 02:46:14,001
[SPEAKER_03]: If you know somebody who needs help getting started with a small business.

2124
02:46:15,822 --> 02:46:18,743
[SPEAKER_08]: Any other questions from the council?

2125
02:46:19,264 --> 02:46:19,764
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Collins.

2126
02:46:22,334 --> 02:46:23,895
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for being here.

2127
02:46:23,975 --> 02:46:25,296
[SPEAKER_05]: Thanks for being one of the last to present.

2128
02:46:26,257 --> 02:46:29,800
[SPEAKER_05]: You've covered most of what I would hope you would cover already.

2129
02:46:29,860 --> 02:46:33,923
[SPEAKER_05]: Obviously, I could go on and on about all the good that your department does in our city.

2130
02:46:33,963 --> 02:46:34,544
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you so much.

2131
02:46:35,745 --> 02:46:44,152
[SPEAKER_05]: Obviously, not all value can be encapsulated in, you know, how much revenue and development and connections you're fostering in the city.

2132
02:46:44,192 --> 02:46:48,676
[SPEAKER_05]: But, you know, just looking at the long page of accomplishments that are supported by outside

2133
02:46:49,170 --> 02:46:56,398
[SPEAKER_05]: grants with the folks that you do have at your disposal, like it really is just staggering how much you're able to do with the resources you have.

2134
02:46:56,458 --> 02:46:58,561
[SPEAKER_05]: So I feel like that always should be said.

2135
02:46:58,581 --> 02:47:04,768
[SPEAKER_05]: I did just, I just wanted to circle back to the climate.

2136
02:47:04,988 --> 02:47:05,989
[SPEAKER_05]: planner position.

2137
02:47:06,129 --> 02:47:11,952
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm just curious if you can speak a little bit more to that, what you're hoping that person will be doing specifically over the next year.

2138
02:47:11,992 --> 02:47:13,453
[SPEAKER_05]: And then if you said it, I missed it.

2139
02:47:13,853 --> 02:47:19,457
[SPEAKER_05]: If you have a plan for if that position will continue after the MAPC grant runs out and how that'll be funded.

2140
02:47:20,533 --> 02:47:29,719
[SPEAKER_03]: So to answer the latter part first, that is the one position that I don't have a plan for how to fund other than to say to the mayor, I'd like to see it in the general fund next year.

2141
02:47:31,200 --> 02:47:36,243
[SPEAKER_03]: I will say that I think there is an argument for either economic development planner or climate planner.

2142
02:47:36,683 --> 02:47:47,130
[SPEAKER_03]: Either one could be funded with CDBG, but we don't have enough money that we're allowed to use for administration to do both of them and the housing planner and the CDBG manager.

2143
02:47:47,450 --> 02:47:49,972
[SPEAKER_03]: There's enough money there for three positions, not for four.

2144
02:47:50,830 --> 02:47:54,134
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, and we've sort of said the economic development planner.

2145
02:47:54,174 --> 02:47:56,276
[SPEAKER_03]: We clearly that has to stay.

2146
02:47:57,097 --> 02:47:59,940
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, also, so that's the one that I'm going to be asking for.

2147
02:47:59,960 --> 02:48:00,000
[SPEAKER_03]: Um,

2148
02:48:02,167 --> 02:48:11,409
[SPEAKER_03]: The grant was truly around policy and making change to zoning and regulations was what they were willing to offer the grant for.

2149
02:48:11,830 --> 02:48:14,070
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's what I wrote that it would do that.

2150
02:48:14,330 --> 02:48:18,271
[SPEAKER_03]: But I also said they would help with our greenhouse gas inventory that we do every year.

2151
02:48:18,331 --> 02:48:20,472
[SPEAKER_03]: They'd help with our annual climate reporting.

2152
02:48:20,892 --> 02:48:25,395
[SPEAKER_03]: they would set up our climate equity council that we outlined in the climate plan.

2153
02:48:26,195 --> 02:48:29,857
[SPEAKER_03]: So those are the main things that I said in the grant that we would do.

2154
02:48:30,878 --> 02:48:34,640
[SPEAKER_03]: We also, I do a bunch of clean energy projects, you know, solar and stuff.

2155
02:48:35,180 --> 02:48:38,102
[SPEAKER_03]: And so I would be hoping that they would be able to help with that.

2156
02:48:38,542 --> 02:48:42,964
[SPEAKER_03]: Some of the building efficiency projects I have been giving to our facilities manager.

2157
02:48:42,984 --> 02:48:47,787
[SPEAKER_03]: And so I partner with our facilities manager on like new HVAC, we're doing

2158
02:48:48,533 --> 02:48:54,597
[SPEAKER_03]: We got, we're doing some studies of like upgrading the HVAC in various buildings and stuff.

2159
02:48:54,677 --> 02:48:59,781
[SPEAKER_03]: And frankly, he's managing those and I'm just sort of like half an ear like, okay, I know who you hire.

2160
02:48:59,861 --> 02:49:00,121
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

2161
02:49:00,141 --> 02:49:00,802
[SPEAKER_03]: I saw the scope.

2162
02:49:00,842 --> 02:49:01,122
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

2163
02:49:01,983 --> 02:49:05,005
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, so, so that's, does that help?

2164
02:49:05,490 --> 02:49:05,970
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, it does.

2165
02:49:06,010 --> 02:49:06,270
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2166
02:49:06,310 --> 02:49:09,991
[SPEAKER_05]: Thanks for outlining the scope of the work of that position over the next year.

2167
02:49:10,051 --> 02:49:15,572
[SPEAKER_05]: And it's great to have a heads up that that's one that will be most likely an ask for fiscal year 25.

2168
02:49:15,932 --> 02:49:18,732
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm glad that this council knows that in advance.

2169
02:49:18,772 --> 02:49:24,273
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, obviously, that's climate resiliency is integral to many of our city's plans.

2170
02:49:24,293 --> 02:49:30,274
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'm glad that we have a full year or two, hopefully partner with you and making sure that that has a place in next year's general.

2171
02:49:30,354 --> 02:49:34,155
[SPEAKER_03]: And there's plenty of climate work that somebody in that role could be doing.

2172
02:49:34,595 --> 02:49:40,959
[SPEAKER_03]: they're going to be focusing more on the regulatory aspects the first year, because that's what the funding was available for.

2173
02:49:40,979 --> 02:49:42,460
[SPEAKER_03]: And I said, well, that's a good start.

2174
02:49:42,620 --> 02:49:43,620
[SPEAKER_03]: Let's get them in the door.

2175
02:49:44,661 --> 02:49:45,361
[SPEAKER_03]: Then we'll keep going.

2176
02:49:46,102 --> 02:49:46,322
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

2177
02:49:47,320 --> 02:49:49,241
[SPEAKER_14]: Councilor say quick question while we have you.

2178
02:49:49,881 --> 02:49:59,943
[SPEAKER_14]: So one of the goals that's stated for this upcoming fiscal year is implementing the redevelopment of better square in alignment with our plans.

2179
02:50:00,063 --> 02:50:10,566
[SPEAKER_14]: And I was just wondering if you were able to give us a general, it doesn't have to be a concrete timeline, but a general timeline of what we might see before us or what your office's goals are.

2180
02:50:10,926 --> 02:50:11,146
[SPEAKER_03]: Right?

2181
02:50:11,326 --> 02:50:13,147
[SPEAKER_03]: So for the Medford square project,

2182
02:50:14,105 --> 02:50:25,289
[SPEAKER_03]: We've been working with Mass Development on the DIF, and part of working with that, the staff from Mass Development have realized that we would really benefit from having a consultant help us write an RFP.

2183
02:50:25,809 --> 02:50:37,512
[SPEAKER_03]: And so they are trying to help us get an out-of-cycle grant, or basically an expansion of that grant that we currently have to add on a consultant who would help with that.

2184
02:50:38,073 --> 02:50:41,914
[SPEAKER_03]: And the thought was that if we get it, it would be starting July 1st.

2185
02:50:42,834 --> 02:50:48,676
[SPEAKER_03]: And honestly, I need an economic development director to help with that project to help lead the project.

2186
02:50:50,077 --> 02:50:57,099
[SPEAKER_03]: So I've kind of we're working slowly on it with the hope that I could bring in some more staff by July 1, a consultant and all.

2187
02:50:57,577 --> 02:50:59,219
[SPEAKER_03]: to actually move that project forward.

2188
02:50:59,499 --> 02:51:04,443
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to write the RFP, we have to figure out what it says, then we have to put it out on the street.

2189
02:51:04,924 --> 02:51:15,433
[SPEAKER_03]: So my best case scenario here is that I get the help that I need, that we do the writing in July and August, and then September, we put it out on the street in mid-September.

2190
02:51:16,021 --> 02:51:24,403
[SPEAKER_03]: And then it's my understanding that that should actually be open for two to three months for people to be able to really develop a concrete proposal for that.

2191
02:51:24,863 --> 02:51:29,144
[SPEAKER_03]: So then that's putting us into mid November to get the results back on it.

2192
02:51:30,024 --> 02:51:31,724
[SPEAKER_03]: And then we'll see what it says.

2193
02:51:32,644 --> 02:51:32,905
[SPEAKER_03]: So.

2194
02:51:33,205 --> 02:51:34,045
[SPEAKER_03]: Great, thank you.

2195
02:51:35,625 --> 02:51:37,085
[SPEAKER_08]: Any additional questions from the council?

2196
02:51:38,866 --> 02:51:39,546
[SPEAKER_08]: Seeing none.

2197
02:51:40,500 --> 02:51:41,340
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you so much, Dr. Hunt.

2198
02:51:41,380 --> 02:51:42,440
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Teresa, for being here.

2199
02:51:42,460 --> 02:51:44,501
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, so we had... Oh, yeah.

2200
02:51:44,541 --> 02:51:50,782
[SPEAKER_03]: Right, I have like five or six boards and commissions, and I will say that Teresa is actually more expert on them than I am.

2201
02:51:50,802 --> 02:51:53,862
[SPEAKER_03]: So I think her first name... Does anyone have any questions on boards or commissions?

2202
02:51:57,683 --> 02:51:58,643
[SPEAKER_06]: Say it to the microphone.

2203
02:51:58,723 --> 02:52:07,265
[SPEAKER_06]: Most of the boards and commissions, which include Historical Commission, Historic District, Conservation Commission, Zoning Board of Appeals,

2204
02:52:08,247 --> 02:52:12,128
[SPEAKER_06]: and the Community Development Board and Bicycle Commission.

2205
02:52:12,208 --> 02:52:12,628
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

2206
02:52:12,708 --> 02:52:14,349
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry, Bicycle Commission, if you're watching.

2207
02:52:15,189 --> 02:52:24,132
[SPEAKER_06]: Most were level funded with the exception of the Zoning Board of Appeals, and that is due to two additional members being appointed to the board.

2208
02:52:24,152 --> 02:52:25,492
[SPEAKER_06]: So that is for their stipends.

2209
02:52:26,833 --> 02:52:30,694
[SPEAKER_06]: Otherwise, I believe Conservation Commission also added an additional person.

2210
02:52:30,714 --> 02:52:34,295
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's just a matter of adding three stipends to our lovely

2211
02:52:35,075 --> 02:52:37,997
[SPEAKER_06]: volunteers in the community helping us progress our projects.

2212
02:52:38,598 --> 02:52:39,678
[SPEAKER_06]: Any questions though?

2213
02:52:40,519 --> 02:52:42,260
[SPEAKER_06]: Seeing none, excellent.

2214
02:52:42,861 --> 02:52:43,581
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you both so much.

2215
02:52:43,621 --> 02:52:44,462
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you all so much.

2216
02:52:44,582 --> 02:52:47,224
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, we will close it out.

2217
02:52:47,264 --> 02:52:54,189
[SPEAKER_08]: We have executive and law, which I think both would be you, Madam Chief of Staff.

2218
02:52:54,589 --> 02:52:58,272
[SPEAKER_08]: Maybe we'll take a beat as everyone is going in opposite directions.

2219
02:53:08,355 --> 02:53:13,438
[SPEAKER_08]: the any of the two counselor, does anyone have a preference whether we start with a law or executive first?

2220
02:53:15,459 --> 02:53:15,839
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

2221
02:53:19,721 --> 02:53:20,922
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Knight, do you?

2222
02:53:22,162 --> 02:53:22,623
[SPEAKER_08]: Are you here?

2223
02:53:22,663 --> 02:53:23,563
[SPEAKER_08]: Are you with us?

2224
02:53:25,564 --> 02:53:26,785
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know where he's somewhere.

2225
02:53:27,225 --> 02:53:28,126
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

2226
02:53:28,686 --> 02:53:32,648
[SPEAKER_08]: When we get back, we'll when people get back to their seats, we'll start with executive.

2227
02:53:32,668 --> 02:53:32,888
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

2228
02:53:37,347 --> 02:53:40,408
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean, yeah.

2229
02:53:40,588 --> 02:53:49,669
[SPEAKER_08]: I can see Councilor Scarpelli walking back towards us.

2230
02:53:49,709 --> 02:53:50,950
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm just going to give him a second to open.

2231
02:53:50,970 --> 02:53:58,151
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

2232
02:54:22,720 --> 02:54:26,745
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, so we are going to executive office expenditure summary is 640,390 down 471,790 less 42.42% versus the prior year.

2233
02:54:26,765 --> 02:54:27,205
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is the...

2234
02:54:40,529 --> 02:54:40,989
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, yeah.

2235
02:54:41,049 --> 02:54:46,612
[SPEAKER_08]: If you want to if you want to just like highlight that I know it says in the summary, but I just want to know because that's a huge number.

2236
02:54:46,672 --> 02:54:50,153
[SPEAKER_07]: So if you want to know why that is certainly thank you, President Morrell.

2237
02:54:50,693 --> 02:54:55,616
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you to the council for this opportunity to discuss the budgets as a point of levity.

2238
02:54:55,696 --> 02:54:58,857
[SPEAKER_07]: Hopefully this will create a little bit of an icebreaker.

2239
02:54:59,517 --> 02:55:04,800
[SPEAKER_07]: These are all hard acts to follow based on tonight, considering I'm here to talk about the executive budget and the law budget.

2240
02:55:05,420 --> 02:55:10,342
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm certainly no comedian, but those who work with me day to day know that I attempt to bring some

2241
02:55:10,837 --> 02:55:13,680
[SPEAKER_07]: smiles to the conversation whenever possible.

2242
02:55:13,760 --> 02:55:15,422
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm attempting to do that here today.

2243
02:55:16,283 --> 02:55:18,266
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm happy to answer any questions you have.

2244
02:55:18,326 --> 02:55:22,430
[SPEAKER_08]: We're going to do executive, and then we'll do law.

2245
02:55:24,190 --> 02:55:30,692
[SPEAKER_07]: On the matter that you raised, President Morrell, the budget for the executive budget is going down what ultimately is 42.4%.

2246
02:55:31,152 --> 02:55:35,373
[SPEAKER_07]: That is, I would call, an artificial decrease.

2247
02:55:35,513 --> 02:55:52,078
[SPEAKER_07]: And the reason that's an artificial decrease, and I would characterize it that way, is because historically, in the last couple years' budgets, we've budgeted some funds for contracted agreements, you know, so that there could be a transfer when a negotiation has settled for a contract.

2248
02:55:52,768 --> 02:56:01,735
[SPEAKER_07]: whereas we have a number of contracts that are currently in negotiations, and we're working towards settlement on obviously all of those.

2249
02:56:02,896 --> 02:56:16,767
[SPEAKER_07]: We have moved those funds out of the executive budget, and we have placed a much larger line inside the budget that is identified on the transmittal letter, which attempts to capture the

2250
02:56:18,306 --> 02:56:26,521
[SPEAKER_07]: what we don't know what the full scope will be ultimately, but the best scope we can determine and ultimately it takes.

2251
02:56:28,720 --> 02:56:36,803
[SPEAKER_07]: it puts more control in the hands of the city council is what it ultimately does because it's in a completely separate budget that the office doesn't have the opportunity to spend without a transfer.

2252
02:56:37,564 --> 02:56:43,486
[SPEAKER_07]: It's really not materially different, but in some ways there are some nuances as to the control that it provides the council.

2253
02:56:43,566 --> 02:56:45,187
[SPEAKER_07]: So just that's all it is.

2254
02:56:45,227 --> 02:56:48,768
[SPEAKER_07]: It's nothing big, it's nothing fancy, it's just what it is.

2255
02:56:49,429 --> 02:56:49,909
[SPEAKER_07]: Great, thank you.

2256
02:56:50,029 --> 02:56:52,730
[SPEAKER_08]: Any other highlights or things you wanna call out before we go to questions?

2257
02:56:54,807 --> 02:56:55,948
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm sorry, any other highlights or things?

2258
02:56:56,068 --> 02:56:57,148
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, I apologize.

2259
02:56:57,228 --> 02:56:59,329
[SPEAKER_07]: I was interpreting that a different way.

2260
02:57:00,570 --> 02:57:01,610
[SPEAKER_07]: Nothing else specifically.

2261
02:57:01,650 --> 02:57:10,815
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, there are some changes as far as there, there's really virtually no changes in terms of the, in terms of the expense side of the budget.

2262
02:57:11,195 --> 02:57:15,597
[SPEAKER_07]: There are some changes to the personnel side of the budget as a result of the non-union COLAs.

2263
02:57:15,617 --> 02:57:16,797
[SPEAKER_07]: Happy to answer any questions.

2264
02:57:17,358 --> 02:57:17,898
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, thank you.

2265
02:57:18,098 --> 02:57:19,019
[SPEAKER_08]: Voter Vice President Behrs.

2266
02:57:20,279 --> 02:57:22,020
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Madam President, thank you, Madam Chief of Staff.

2267
02:57:24,827 --> 02:57:29,329
[SPEAKER_20]: two questions are, well, I guess it may be three.

2268
02:57:30,429 --> 02:57:35,151
[SPEAKER_20]: My first one is, on the negotiated salaries, it's gone from that 500K to 3 million.

2269
02:57:36,332 --> 02:57:38,032
[SPEAKER_20]: Obviously, that's a huge increase.

2270
02:57:38,153 --> 02:57:41,134
[SPEAKER_20]: Is that reflective, is that a best estimate?

2271
02:57:41,954 --> 02:57:45,796
[SPEAKER_20]: Are we overestimating with the hopes that it will be, you know,

2272
02:57:47,001 --> 02:57:48,182
[SPEAKER_20]: It's a $3 million thing.

2273
02:57:48,222 --> 02:57:49,842
[SPEAKER_20]: We're not sure we're actually gonna spend.

2274
02:57:50,823 --> 02:57:55,645
[SPEAKER_20]: And as we've highlighted, I think there's priorities that council would like to see funded.

2275
02:57:55,665 --> 02:58:04,908
[SPEAKER_20]: That seems like the one area of the budget where it's not saying, we know this is exactly how much we're gonna have to spend on these positions and these expenses.

2276
02:58:05,168 --> 02:58:06,409
[SPEAKER_20]: Is that fungible at all?

2277
02:58:06,589 --> 02:58:11,111
[SPEAKER_20]: Or are you putting it there because it's really like a solid estimate of what the cost could be?

2278
02:58:12,327 --> 02:58:21,713
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is hard to really truly answer the question and really be fair to any scenario that might arise.

2279
02:58:23,834 --> 02:58:25,555
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a lot of different contracts that are open.

2280
02:58:26,656 --> 02:58:30,318
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not just a percentage potential increase to those contracts.

2281
02:58:30,398 --> 02:58:32,259
[SPEAKER_07]: There are other areas.

2282
02:58:32,299 --> 02:58:37,202
[SPEAKER_07]: There could be an increase that's agreed upon for call it longevity.

2283
02:58:37,552 --> 02:58:38,873
[SPEAKER_07]: an increase that's agreed upon.

2284
02:58:38,893 --> 02:58:45,156
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not saying we would or wouldn't, I'm just saying that there's so many different categories for me to be able to truly answer the question.

2285
02:58:45,536 --> 02:58:48,177
[SPEAKER_07]: We did our best faith estimate on this.

2286
02:58:49,778 --> 02:58:51,699
[SPEAKER_07]: So yes, it could go up, it could go down.

2287
02:58:52,039 --> 02:59:05,426
[SPEAKER_07]: The reality is there's no like set number, but what we are attempting to do is present what we need to capture in the budget so that there is a placeholder, so we don't go back to our past

2288
02:59:06,108 --> 02:59:08,329
[SPEAKER_07]: historical challenges of a structural deficit.

2289
02:59:08,529 --> 02:59:10,370
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, okay.

2290
02:59:12,031 --> 02:59:19,195
[SPEAKER_20]: Second piece is I know there's some staff positions that are partially funded through the one time ARPA federal grant funding.

2291
02:59:19,215 --> 02:59:23,938
[SPEAKER_20]: Is your plan to continue those positions in future budgets or is that really like

